n&nbsp;Latin America: The Beginning or the End of Latin America&rsquo;s &lsquo;Continental Integration&rsquo;? by&nbsp;Paul Isbell Centre for Transatlantic Relations Johns Hopkins University-SAIS and&nbsp;Kimberly A. Nolan Garc&iacute;a Centro de Investigaci&oacute;n y Docencia Econ&oacute;micas (CIDE)","body":"<p>This paper investigates the development of regionalism and inter-regionalism in Latin America as pertains to trade relations, one of the key drivers of regional integration in the region. The paper develops the outlines of the thesis that &lsquo;Latin America&rsquo; or &lsquo;South America&rsquo; no longer provide the optimal geography for constituting an appropriate region, and that new 'ocean basin regions' offer more promising regional and interregional trajectories for Latin American countries to pursue than do their currently conceived land-based &lsquo;trade regions&rsquo;. By &lsquo;re-mapping&rsquo; national figures for bilateral commercial trade culled from the UNCOMTRADE data set, we provide initial quantitative evidence of new Latin American regional trade dynamics emerging within the continent&rsquo;s two flanking ocean basin regions &ndash; the Pacific Basin and the Atlantic Basin &ndash; where new forms of &lsquo;non-hegemonic&rsquo; and &lsquo;maritime-centered&rsquo; regionalisms are being articulated and developed. The paper concludes that new &lsquo;ocean basin regionalisms&rsquo; offer Latin America alternative options for pursuing regional trade agreements and other forms of inter-regional trade integration which, while remaining complementary to the current sub-continental and continental regionalisms, and could become a new guiding frame for Latin American regionalism.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"137","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":false,"type":"0","created":"2015-12-01 12:10:00","modified":"2016-02-05 19:11:13"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"180","content_id":"1595","type":"1","file_name":"1595-Regionalism and interregionalism in Latin America. The Beginning or the end of Latin America's Continental Integration.pdf","description":"Regionalism and interregionalism\r\nin Latin America: The Beginning or the End of Latin\r\nAmerica\u2019s \u2018Continental Integration\u2019?","created":"2015-12-01 12:17:07","modified":"2015-12-01 12:17:07"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"7337","content_id":"1595","tag_id":"20","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"20","code":"economy-and-finance","name":"Economy and finance","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"A85CA0","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-09-27 09:57:02"}},{"id":"7331","content_id":"1595","tag_id":"141","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"141","code":"latin-america","name":"Latin America","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:43","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:43"}},{"id":"7332","content_id":"1595","tag_id":"252","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"252","code":"north-america","name":"north america","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7333","content_id":"1595","tag_id":"287","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"287","code":"interregionalism","name":"interregionalism","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7334","content_id":"1595","tag_id":"289","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"289","code":"cidob","name":"cidob","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7335","content_id":"1595","tag_id":"153","order":"5","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"153","code":"centro-de-investigacion-y-docencia-economicas-ac-cide","name":"Centro de Investigaci\u00f3n y Docencia Econ\u00f3micas A.C. (CIDE)","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-10 15:01:11","modified":"2013-12-10 15:01:11"}},{"id":"7336","content_id":"1595","tag_id":"150","order":"6","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"7337","content_id":"1595","tag_id":"20","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"20","code":"economy-and-finance","name":"Economy and finance","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"A85CA0","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-09-27 09:57:02"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"1532","code":"africa-and-the-eu","user_id":"1","title":"Africa and the EU","abstract":"Working paper The EU and Africa:&nbsp;Regionalism and interregionalism beyond institutions, by&nbsp;Nicoletta Pirozzi,&nbsp;Istituto Affari Internazionali (IAI)&nbsp;and Andr&eacute;as Gods&auml;ter,&nbsp;University of Pretoria (UP)","body":"<p>This paper aims at mapping relevant trends of regionalism and interregionalism in and between Europe and &nbsp;Africa, by looking at the historical evolution and in light of recent developments. The analysis focuses on institutionalized regionalism and interregionalism between the European Union (EU) and the African Union (AU), as well as regional organizations in Southern, West and East Africa in the three sectors of trade; security; and environment. It also goes beyond by addressing and comparing formal and informal, state and non-state, patterns of integration at regional and transnational levels.<\/p>\r\n<p>The paper concludes that the EU and AU present many commonalties in terms of institutional architecture. Nevertheless, if we look at the reality of their achievements, it emerges that the two organizations evolved at different pace, with the AU lagging behind, also due to the fact that the integration process in the two regions is confronted with different challenges.In terms of interregional relations, it appears that the EU has heavily influenced the development of regionalism in Africa mainly through teaching and support. The relationship between the EU and African regions is fundamentally characterized by the former influencing regional policy of, and providing funds and capacity building to, the latter.<\/p>","views":"254","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2015-11-17 12:30:00","modified":"2016-02-08 14:09:42"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"178","content_id":"1532","type":"1","file_name":"1532-EU-Africa.pdf","description":"The EU and Africa: Regionalism and interregionalism beyond institutions\r\n","created":"2015-11-17 12:30:47","modified":"2015-11-17 12:30:47"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"7330","content_id":"1532","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"7324","content_id":"1532","tag_id":"287","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"287","code":"interregionalism","name":"interregionalism","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7325","content_id":"1532","tag_id":"286","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"286","code":"eu","name":"eu","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7326","content_id":"1532","tag_id":"137","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"137","code":"european-union","name":"European Union","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:16:06","modified":"2013-10-25 10:16:06"}},{"id":"7327","content_id":"1532","tag_id":"140","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"140","code":"africa","name":"Africa","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:33","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:33"}},{"id":"7328","content_id":"1532","tag_id":"178","order":"5","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"178","code":"university-of-pretoria","name":"University of Pretoria","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2014-04-24 14:52:42","modified":"2014-04-24 14:52:42"}},{"id":"7329","content_id":"1532","tag_id":"150","order":"6","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"7330","content_id":"1532","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"1531","code":"the-arab-region-and-latin-america","user_id":"1","title":"The Arab region and Latin America","abstract":"Working paper Actors and opportunities: Interregional processes in the Arab region and Latin America and the Caribbean, by&nbsp;Anna Ayuso and Santiago Villar,&nbsp;CIDOB, and&nbsp;Camila Pastor and Miguel Fuentes,&nbsp;CIDE","body":"<p>This paper analyses the links between Latin America and the Caribbean (LAC) and Arab countries. The relations between regional organisations in LAC and their peers in North Africa and the Arab world are still fairly nascent and represent a much understudied area of interregionalism in the global order. However, three cases of recent institutional rapprochement between LAC regional organisations (i.e. CELAC, UNASUR and Mercosur) and a North African and Arab world regional institution (i.e. the LAS) are remarkable. The re-launching of South-South cooperation in recent decades in a multipolar context has favoured rapprochement between LAC and the Arab world. Despite the fact that both regions are not a priority for each other, relations and exchanges have grown constantly over the last 10-12 years, accompanied by a progressive institutionalisation of high-level political dialogue. This study aims to identify and analyse the main drivers behind this multi-layered interregionalism as well as the obstacles in its way by examining how it is fostered by political, economic and social state and non-state actors.<\/p>","views":"145","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":false,"type":"0","created":"2015-11-17 12:28:00","modified":"2016-02-03 18:40:54"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"