e Caribbean have given rise to overlapping regionalist projects, where the overlapping of competences is more problematic than that of membership. Also, Latin American and Caribbean regionalisms have constantly evolved in terms of strategies and organisations. This has generated a number of interregional institutionalized mechanisms between the EU and Latin America and the Caribbean, but the current structure seems in need for reform.<\/p>","views":"195","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2015-11-17 12:25:00","modified":"2016-02-08 04:57:40"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"176","content_id":"1530","type":"1","file_name":"1530-LA-EU.pdf","description":"EU-Latin America and Caribbean Inter-regional relations: complexity and change","created":"2015-11-17 12:25:35","modified":"2015-11-17 12:25:35"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"7315","content_id":"1530","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"7310","content_id":"1530","tag_id":"287","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"287","code":"interregionalism","name":"interregionalism","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7311","content_id":"1530","tag_id":"141","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"141","code":"latin-america","name":"Latin America","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:43","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:43"}},{"id":"7312","content_id":"1530","tag_id":"138","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"138","code":"europe","name":"Europe","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:16:35","modified":"2013-10-25 10:16:35"}},{"id":"7313","content_id":"1530","tag_id":"286","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"286","code":"eu","name":"eu","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7314","content_id":"1530","tag_id":"150","order":"5","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"7315","content_id":"1530","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"1529","code":"latin-america-and-sub-saharan-africa","user_id":"1","title":"Latin America and Sub-Saharan Africa","abstract":"Working paper Regionalism and Interregionalism: The case of Latin America and Sub-Saharan Africa, by&nbsp;Frank Mattheis,&nbsp;Centre for the Study of Governance Innovation, University of Pretoria","body":"<p>In their extra-regional outreach Latin America and Sub-Saharan Africa rarely make each other a priority. However, since the end of the Cold War there has been an increasing amount of political efforts to strengthen ties on a region-to-region basis. This paper argues that this rapprochement has been facilitated by the emergence of two regional projects following a similar logic in a post-Cold War context: the Southern African Development Community and the Common Market of the Southern Cone. At the same time, both projects face serious limitations of actorness that are illustrative of the confined space for interregionalism across the South Atlantic. An analysis of the formalised initiatives on political, economic and trade issues between the two regions concludes that these are characterised by transregional and partly pure forms of interregionalism and that most initiatives are heavily shaped by the leading role of Brazil.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Download the working paper here:&nbsp;<\/strong><\/p>","views":"74","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":false,"type":"0","created":"2015-11-17 12:21:00","modified":"2016-02-03 18:41:00"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"175","content_id":"1529","type":"1","file_name":"1529-LA-Africa.pdf","description":"Regionalism and Interregionalism: The case of Latin America and Sub-Saharan Africa","created":"2015-11-17 12:22:01","modified":"2015-11-17 12:22:01"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"7309","content_id":"1529","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"7303","content_id":"1529","tag_id":"287","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"287","code":"interregionalism","name":"interregionalism","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7304","content_id":"1529","tag_id":"178","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"178","code":"university-of-pretoria","name":"University of Pretoria","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2014-04-24 14:52:42","modified":"2014-04-24 14:52:42"}},{"id":"7305","content_id":"1529","tag_id":"189","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"189","code":"govinn","name":"govinn","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7306","content_id":"1529","tag_id":"141","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"141","code":"latin-america","name":"Latin America","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:43","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:43"}},{"id":"7307","content_id":"1529","tag_id":"140","order":"5","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"140","code":"africa","name":"Africa","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:33","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:33"}},{"id":"7308","content_id":"1529","tag_id":"150","order":"6","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"7309","content_id":"1529","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"1528","code":"europe-and-north-america","user_id":"1","title":"Europe and North America","abstract":"Working paper Regional and Interregional Interactions in Europe, North America and across the North Atlantic, by&nbsp;Riccardo Alcaro,&nbsp;Istituto Affari Internazionali, and&nbsp;Patrick Reilly,&nbsp;German Marshall Fund of the United States","body":"<p>If we figured regionalism as a continuum from rudimental regional interaction to very sophisticated forms of it, Europe stands on this latter end while North America barely makes it to the middle point. The imbalance in the degree of regionalization on the two northern shores of the Atlantic explains the non-existent region-to-region interaction. Interregionalism has thus little to say about Europe and North America, although &lsquo;quasi-interregionalism&rsquo; (i.e. country-region relations) has here some of its most advanced manifestations. The case of US-Europe relations actually goes beyond quasi-interregionalism and displays traits that are more characteristic of regionalism than anything else. A comparison of regionalism in Europe and North America is therefore invariably destined to be an exercise involving a third, bicontinental region: the West.<\/p>","views":"604","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":false,"type":"0","created":"2015-11-17 12:14:00","modified":"2016-02-08 09:30:04"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"174","content_id":"1528","type":"1","file_name":"1528-NA-EU.pdf","description":"Regional and Interregional Interactions in Europe, North America and across the North Atlantic","created":"2015-11-17 12:15:30","modified":"2015-11-17 12:15:30"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"7302","content_id":"1528","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"7301","content_id":"1528","tag_id":"150","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"7302","content_id":"1528","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"1519","code":"north-america-and-africa","user_id":"1","title":"North America and Africa","abstract":"Working paper Interregional Relations between North America and Africa, by&nbsp;John Kotsopoulos,&nbsp;University of Pretoria, and&nbsp;Madeleine Goerg,&nbsp;German Marshall Fund","body":"<p>This paper explores the extent of interregional cooperation between North America and Africa in the area of development.&nbsp; Given the relative lack of such relationships between regional organisations on the two continents, the paper uses quasi-interregionalism as a framework to instead explore relations between the United States and African regional organisations and similarly Canada and African regional organisations. Using primary documents and interviews, the paper also explores where and if cooperation between the U.S. and Canada is evident in interactions with African regional entities. The results are marginal at this stage, but do point to the continuing rise in importance of African regional organisations like the African Union as increasingly prominent interlocutors.<\/p>","views":"139","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":false,"type":"0","created":"2015-11-17 12:11:00","modified":"2016-02-04 12:41:50"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"173","content_id":"1519","type":"1","file_name":"1519-NA - Africa.pdf","description":"Interregional Relations between North America and Africa","created":"2015-11-17 12:11:46","modified":"2015-11-17 12:11:46"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"7300","content_id":"1519","tag_id":"20","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"20","code":"economy-and-finance","name":"Economy and finance","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"A85CA0","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-09-27 09:57:02"}},{"id":"7297","content_id":"1519","tag_id":"140","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"140","code":"africa","name":"Africa","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:33","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:33"}},{"id":"7298","content_id":"1519","tag_id":"252","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"252","code":"north-america","name":"north america","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7299","content_id":"1519","tag_id":"150","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"7300","content_id":"1519","tag_id":"20","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"20","code":"economy-and-finance","name":"Economy and finance","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"A85CA0","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-09-27 09:57:02"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"1518","code":"brussels-a-transformed-atlantic-space","user_id":"1","title":"Brussels: A transformed Atlantic Space","abstract":"Final dissemination event in Brussels:&nbsp;A transformed Atlantic Space: Emerging trends and future scenarios for Europe","body":"<p><strong>A transformed Atlantic Space: Emerging trends and future scenarios for Europe<\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p>Join us in the final dissemination event of the Atlantic Future project in Brussels.&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p>We are pleased to invite you to the event &ldquo;A transformed Atlantic Space: Emerging trends and future scenarios for Europe&rdquo; on 10 December in Brussels.<\/p>\r\n<p>The event will mark the end of the research project <a href=\"..\/..\/..\/..\/\">Atlantic Future<\/a>. Our experts will provide new perspectives on the Atlantic space and on the policy approaches to this region, and will present the new web-based &ldquo;Atlas of the Atlantic&rdquo;.<\/p>\r\n<p>The Atlantic can be considered the cradle of modern globalisation, a space where links between peoples, nations and economies started first to transcend their regional contexts on a large scale. As globalisation enters a new phase and as global challenges such as the economic crises, food security, terrorism, climate change or energy scarcity become more urgent, the states and regions around the Atlantic look at their counterparts across the ocean with renewed interest.<\/p>\r\n<p>Join us in what promises to be an engaging discussion.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Date<\/strong>: 10 December 2015<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Time<\/strong>: 9.15-14.15<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Venue<\/strong>: Center for European Policy Studies (CEPS), Working Party Room - 3rd floor, Place du Congr&egrave;s, 1 -1000 Brussels<\/p>\r\n<p>To confirm your attendance, please confirm at <a href=\"mailto:activitats@cidob.org\">activitats@cidob.org<\/a><\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Agenda attached<\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"707","shares":"1","tweets":"4","mails":"1","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"1","created":"2015-11-17 12:07:00","modified":"2016-02-08 14:09:30"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":"1518","datetime":"2015-12-10 09:00:00","country":"Belgium","city":"Brussels","address":"Congresplaats 1, Brussels (CEPS)","map":""},"Resource":[{"id":"181","content_id":"1518","type":"1","file_name":"1518-ATLANTIC FUTURE_A transformed Atlantic Space_Brussels.pdf","description":"Brussels agenda","created":"2015-12-02 19:52:47","modified":"2015-12-02 19:52:47"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"7165","content_id":"1518","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"7162","content_id":"1518","tag_id":"137","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"137","code":"european-union","name":"European Union","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:16:06","modified":"2013-10-25 10:16:06"}},{"id":"7163","content_id":"1518","tag_id":"283","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"283","code":"brussels","name":"brussels","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7164","content_id":"1518","tag_id":"43","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"43","code":"policy","name":"Policy","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 10:04:43","modified":"2013-09-27 10:04:43"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"7165","content_id":"1518","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"1517","code":"dc-the-future-of-the-atlantic-hemisphere","user_id":"1","title":"DC: The Future of the Atlantic Hemisphere","abstract":"Dissemination event in Washington DC","body":"<p>Globalization is not just about the rise of the Asian Hemisphere. The four Atlantic continents are connecting in many surprising ways via energy, goods, services, people and ideas. Join us for the culmination of a three-year study by research institutes on the four Atlantic continents mapping trends, perspectives and interregional dynamics between Europe, Africa, and the Americas.&nbsp; Our institutes will present the results of our research, charting new connections and presenting new Atlantic connections. We will unveil a new web-based \"Atlas of the Atlantic\" and feature speakers from all four Atlantic continents on the rise of the ''Atlantic Hemisphere.''<\/p>\r\n<p>The Kenney Auditorium <br \/>The Johns Hopkins University's School of Advanced International Studies <br \/>1740 Massachusetts Avenue, NW <br \/>Washington, DC 20036<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Agenda:&nbsp;<\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p><strong>9:00<\/strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Welcome:&nbsp;<em>The Future of the Atlantic Hemisphere: Presentation of Final Report from the Atlantic Future Project<\/em><\/strong><\/p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Dan Hamilton<\/strong>, Center for Transatlantic Relations, Johns Hopkins SAIS<\/li>\r\n<li><strong>Anna Ayuso<\/strong>, CIDOB, Barcelona, Spain<\/li>\r\n<li><strong>Alfredo Valladao<\/strong>, HEM Business School, Casablanca, Morocco<\/li>\r\n<li><strong>Frank Mattheis<\/strong>, University of Pretoria, South Africa<\/li>\r\n<li><strong>R. Andreas Kraemer<\/strong>, Founder and Director Emeritus of Ecologic Institute<\/li>\r\n<\/ul>\r\n<p><strong>9:45<\/strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Panel I:&nbsp;<em>The Future of Energy in the Atlantic Hemisphere<\/em><\/strong><\/p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Paul Isbell<\/strong>, CAF Energy Fellow, CTR\/SAIS<\/li>\r\n<li><strong>Vicente L&oacute;pez-Ibor Mayor,&nbsp;<\/strong>President, Lightsource; Former Commissioner of the National Energy Commission of Spain<\/li>\r\n<li><strong>David Livingston,&nbsp;<\/strong>Carnegie Endowment for International Peace<\/li>\r\n<\/ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<strong>10:45<em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <\/em><\/strong><em>Coffee Break<\/em><\/p>\r\n<p><strong>11:00<\/strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/em>Panel II<em>&nbsp;Economic Growth and Human Development in the Atlantic Hemisphere<\/em><\/strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;<\/strong><strong>Moderated by Tim Ridout,&nbsp;<\/strong>GMF&nbsp;<strong>&nbsp;<\/strong><\/p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Timothy Hobson<\/strong>, Funda&ccedil;&atilde;o Getulio Vargas, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil<\/li>\r\n<li><strong>E. Anthony Wayne<\/strong>, former US Ambassador to Mexico and Argentina; former Asst. Secretary of State for Business and Economic Affairs<\/li>\r\n<li>&nbsp;former US Ambassador to Mexico and Argentina; former Asst. Secretary of State for Business and Economic Affairs<\/li>\r\n<li><strong>David Rice<\/strong>, Director, Tony Elumelu Foundation Africapitalism Institute, Nigeria<em>&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/em><\/li>\r\n<li><strong>Eveline Herfkens<\/strong>, Former Minister of Development Cooperation of The Netherlands<\/li>\r\n<li><strong>Robert Dixon<\/strong>, Global Environmental Facility, the World Bank<br \/>&nbsp;<\/li>\r\n<\/ul>\r\n<p><strong>12:00<\/strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lunch<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<strong>12:45<\/strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Panel III:&nbsp;<em>Issues of Resources and Sustainability in the Atlantic Basin<\/em><\/strong><\/p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Tanja Srebotnjak<\/strong>, Hixon Professorship of Sustainable Environmental Design, Harvey Mudd College<\/li>\r\n<li><strong>Juan Jos&eacute; Daboub,&nbsp;<\/strong>Former Managing Director of the World Bank&nbsp;<\/li>\r\n<\/ul>\r\n<p><strong>1:45 pm<\/strong>&nbsp;<strong>Panel IV:&nbsp;<em>Evolving Human Security Challenges in the Atlantic Hemisphere<\/em><\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;<\/strong><strong>Moderated by Johanna Mendelson Forman,&nbsp;<\/strong>Stimson Center, Member of the Scientific Advisory Panel of Atlantic Future<\/p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Alfredo Valladao<\/strong>, HEM<\/li>\r\n<li><strong>Nancy Brune<\/strong>, Center for New American Security<\/li>\r\n<li><strong>Frank Mattheis<\/strong>, University of Pretoria, South Africa<\/li>\r\n<li><strong>In&ecirc;s Pereira da Costa Sousa<\/strong>, Funda&ccedil;&atilde;o Getulio Vargas, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil<\/li>\r\n<\/ul>\r\n<p><strong>2:45 pm<\/strong>&nbsp;<strong>Conclusion<\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;<\/strong><\/p>","views":"135","shares":"2","tweets":"1","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":false,"type":"1","created":"2015-11-17 11:50:00","modified":"2016-02-08 14:09:53"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":"1517","datetime":"2015-12-01 09:00:00","country":"United States","city":"Washington DC","address":"The Kenney Auditorium\r\nThe Johns Hopkins University's School of Advanced International Studies\r\n1740 Massachusetts Avenue, NW\r\nWashington, DC 20036","map":""},"Resource":[{"id":"179","content_id":"1517","type":"1","file_name":"1517-Atlantic_Future_Agenda_Dec_1.pdf","description":"The Future of the Atlantic Hemisphere_Agenda_Washington DC","created":"2015-11-20 14:45:12","modified":"2015-11-20 14:45:12"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"6993","content_id":"1517","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"6990","content_id":"1517","tag_id":"125","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"125","code":"johns-hopkins-university-jhu","name":"Johns Hopkins University (JHU)","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-30 10:19:12","modified":"2013-09-30 10:19:12"}},{"id":"6991","content_id":"1517","tag_id":"174","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"174","code":"ecologic-institute","name":"ecologic institute","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"6992","content_id":"1517","tag_id":"21","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"21","code":"security","name":"Security","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"C31F4A","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:08:37"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"6993","content_id":"1517","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"1265","code":"atlantic-voices-with-driss-ksikes","user_id":"1","title":"Atlantic Voices with Driss Ksikes","abstract":"A view of the Atlantic from Morocco.","body":"<p><em>Born in Casablanca in 1968, Driss Ksikes is a Moroccan well-known intellectual figure. Journalist, writer, internationally renowned playwright, he is professor of media and culture and director of Cesem, HEM Business school research centre in Rabat and its media platform, economia.ma. He used to be editor of liberal Moroccan magazine, TelQuel. Among his late published essays: Le m&eacute;tier d&rsquo;intellectuel, dialogues avec quinze penseurs du Maroc, Coll. Presses de l&rsquo;Universit&eacute; Citoyenne, Ed. En toutes lettres, 2014. Co-founder of Averroes encounters in Rabat, of Dabateatr citoyen and Le Collectif du vivre ensemble, among other cultural initiatives, Ksikes shares his time between research, writing and developing platforms of debates and creativity, both within HEM and in the public space.<\/em><\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Q - What opportunities the Atlantic does offer to Morocco?<\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p>A - It is, first, noteworthy, that Morocco has a voluntarily multi-oriented &ldquo;policy&rdquo;. Politically, considerations of post-colonial autonomy and bonds with emerging powers are added to the need of classical powers&rsquo;s support to help in the western Sahara conflict. Economically, while being to a large extent dependent on European market and funds \/ investments from Gulf countries, Morocco is more and more engaged in developing its west african backyard, leading hopefully a security, logistic, innovation and investment regional hub. Its booming industrial and services policies are not yet full-fledged but could potentially be directed that way.<\/p>\r\n<p>The vertical, Afro-European axis, added to American partial Alliance for strategic purposes give theoretically to the Moroccan Atlantic orientations enough reasons to look necessary. The need also to strike a balance between western values and Islamic heritage, as a landmark of the regime, make also of the Atlantic space a good resort for Morocco. Last but not least, while considering security as one of its main political assets, Morocco is necessarily hankering for NATO partnerships and bilateral conventions to develop its role as a regional trustworthy ally for the western major countries and a reliable north African watch-dog.<\/p>\r\n<p>Finally, looking westwards, more than ever before, helps Morocco reconsider its historical and continental heritage, its maritime unused assets and its institutional and diplomatic flaws that he needs badly to build a genuine international policy.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Q &ndash; What is the view of the Atlantic from the North of Africa?<\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p>A - From a North African perspective, where Maghreb, the closer space, is a big failure, the Atlantic is seen as a far-fetched idea, and even physically as a far away world to put together. It is also considered as a sum of scattered spaces with divergent interests and perspectives. It is also seen as an unbalanced space where the interdependencies between the North and the South are mostly unilateral.&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p>If we are to rationalize things a bit, the Atlantic is perceived as a threatening alternative to the Mediterranean, which never managed to re-emerge as a regional space. The Atlantic is actually first identified to the North Atlantic order, and more and more, since TTIP launching, to Europe-US alliance. Having weak maritime power and culture, North Africa is in a certain sense mainly considering an Atlantic alternative view from a continental point of view. Thus having a blossoming African policy is seen as the first step to a southern input into the Atlantic. Being also the source of some terrorist, drug and migrant flows, the Atlantic is looked upon as a threatening space to control and regulate, for themselves and their northern partners.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Q - <\/strong><strong>What are the main challenges for the emergence of the Atlantic space?<\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p>A - In the current context where the European Union and United States are planning to sign TTIP, where EU is more than ever weakened by migrant and asylum seeking floods, and where, for anti-terrorist reasons and to counter new Russian expansionism, NATO is recovering its old prerogatives, many doubts are rising about possible re-shaping of the Atlantic. When this project, &ldquo;Atlantic Future&rdquo;, was tailored, four years ago, the international context was not as tense and conflict-bound as it looks today. To make the perspective look again attainable, we need more visionary and sound leaders who would know how to put peace, solidarity, social inclusion and economic development on the top of political priorities.<\/p>\r\n<p>Besides, to make it possible for this space to emerge, there should be an earnest interest in southern countries development not only as tactics but as a necessity and a must. There should be also awareness that each country has to make internally of democracy a real horizon not a fake mask for external and media consumption. And there should be more strategic efforts to develop strong economic ties between sub regions, the Maghreb being the most uncertain of all. Without all these prerequisites, I doubt an Atlantic space could anyhow emerge.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Download the Atlantic Voices here:<\/strong><\/p>","views":"174","shares":"1","tweets":"2","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":false,"type":"0","created":"2015-11-04 08:22:00","modified":"2016-02-08 14:10:00"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"172","cont