:"1106","tag_id":"256","order":"8","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"256","code":"values","name":"values","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7407","content_id":"1106","tag_id":"150","order":"9","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"7408","content_id":"1106","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"1119","code":"rio-de-janeiro-opportunities-for-brazil","user_id":"1","title":"Rio de Janeiro: Opportunities for Brazil","abstract":"Rio de Janeiro (Brazil), 16 November 2015\r\nATLANTIC FUTURE will hold an event in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, to disseminate project results and to discuss opportunities for Brazil in the Atlantic. ","body":"<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p>The event will be an excellent opportunity to hold discussions with eminent experts on the opportunities the Atlantic holds for Brazil and the future of the Atlantic.<\/p>","views":"34","shares":"0","tweets":"2","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":false,"type":"1","created":"2015-10-02 11:54:00","modified":"2016-02-05 12:47:17"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":"1119","datetime":"2015-11-16 09:00:00","country":"Brazil","city":"Rio de Janeiro","address":"","map":""},"Resource":[],"ContentTag":[{"id":"6502","content_id":"1119","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"6501","content_id":"1119","tag_id":"36","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"36","code":"events","name":"Events","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"995B31","created":"2013-09-27 09:58:37","modified":"2013-09-27 09:58:37"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"6502","content_id":"1119","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"946","code":"9th-pan-european-conference-on-iirr","user_id":"1","title":"9th Pan-European Conference on IIRR","abstract":"ATLANTIC FUTURE will participate in the 9th Pan-European Conference on International Relations &ndash; The Worlds of Violence next September in Sicily. The conference is organised by the European International Studies Association (EISA) and the University of Catania.\r\nResearchers Frank Mattheis (GovInn, University of Pretoria), Gian Luca Gardini (School of Business and Economics, University Erlangen-N&uuml;rnberg) and Andr&eacute;s Malamud (IPRI and University of Lisboa) will present ATLANTIC FUTURE research results in the following sections:\r\n&nbsp;","body":"<p><strong>Power Shifts and International Institutions<\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p>A shifting distribution of international power is a fundamental contemporary trend. Emerging countries are changing the global balance of power, altering the character of the global political economy, and bringing new interests and ideas into the international arena. At the same time, international politics is characterised by a growing number of international institutions. These range from formal intergovernmental organizations like the UN Security Council or the Financial Stability Board, to informal clubs like the G7, BRICS and IBSA forums, to commonly accepted ideas and norms, and even to transnational private institutions like the International Accounting Standards Board. Few of these institutions are unaffected by the economic shift towards emerging markets or by the power shift between national governments. The impact of a changed power balance can occur within the institutions themselves, by altering their status and effectiveness, or by changing the relations of international institutions to each other. Moreover, these institutions have important effects on the global economy and on inter-state relations, including their propensity for violence.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Maritime Security<\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p>Maritime Security is perhaps the latest addition to the international security vocabulary. Several security actors, including NATO, the EU, the AU and the UK have launched maritime security strategies recently which foregrounds the salience of the theme. At the same time security studies is gradually discovering the importance of the maritime dimension and researchers from around the world have launched investigations that go beyond the traditional concerns with naval strategy and sea battles. This section aims to discuss a range of emerging themes related to maritime security, including perspectives on core maritime issues, such as piracy, maritime crime, human trafficking, illegal fishing, boundary disputes, port security, and maritime security sector reform. The objective will be to build connection between traditional security studies, institutionalist research and contemporary critical security studies.<\/p>\r\n<p>More information: <a href=\"http:\/\/www.paneuropeanconference.org\/2015\/\">http:\/\/www.paneuropeanconference.org\/2015\/<\/a><\/p>","views":"41","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":false,"type":"1","created":"2015-09-26 09:00:00","modified":"2016-01-10 04:04:48"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":"946","datetime":"2015-09-23 09:00:00","country":"Italy","city":"Sicily","address":"","map":""},"Resource":[],"ContentTag":[{"id":"5535","content_id":"946","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"5534","content_id":"946","tag_id":"208","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"208","code":"maritime-security","name":"maritime security","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"5535","content_id":"946","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"945","code":"conference-atlantic-communities","user_id":"1","title":"Conference \u201cAtlantic Communities\u201d","abstract":"ATLANTIC FUTURE will participate in the I International Conference &ldquo;Atlantic Communities: Translation, Mobility, Hospitality&rdquo; to be held in Vigo, Spain on 17-18 September 2015.","body":"<p>The Atlantic Ocean has historically played a major role in the relationship between the &ldquo;Old World&rdquo; and the &ldquo;New World&rdquo;, both perceived as a geographical and cultural divide between continents but also functioning as a space of transit, mobility and hospitality. Accordingly, the history and culture of the diverse countries and continents that border the Atlantic tends to be studied either in terms of regional influence within the framework of a geopolitics, or as a series of exchanges and encounters between the different people and territories on or near the Atlantic shores.<\/p>\r\n<p>This conference seeks to bring together scholars from across the social sciences and the humanities in order both to extend the focus of these approaches and to suggest new ways of thinking about what binds and what separates the communities and individuals that inhabit the complex social and cultural spaces on both sides of the Atlantic.<\/p>\r\n<p>For more information on the conference, visit the site <a href=\"http:\/\/atlanticcommunitiesconference.blogspot.com.es\/\"><strong>http:\/\/atlanticcommunitiesconference.blogspot.com.es\/<\/strong><\/a><\/p>","views":"206","shares":"1","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":false,"type":"1","created":"2015-09-17 09:00:00","modified":"2016-02-01 17:21:39"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":"945","datetime":"2015-09-17 09:00:00","country":"Spain","city":"Vigo","address":"","map":""},"Resource":[],"ContentTag":[{"id":"5527","content_id":"945","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"5525","content_id":"945","tag_id":"147","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"147","code":"international-relations","name":"international relations","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-11-18 11:32:59","modified":"2013-11-18 11:32:59"}},{"id":"5526","content_id":"945","tag_id":"5","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"5","code":"atlantic-space","name":"Atlantic space","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 09:55:08","modified":"2013-09-27 09:55:08"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"5527","content_id":"945","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"1113","code":"future-environment-and-resource-scenarios","user_id":"1","title":"Future Environment and Resource Scenarios","abstract":"This paper by Elizabeth Tedsen, Christoph Stefes, Lucy Smith, and Katherine Weingartner at Ecologic Institute examines the dynamics of four key environment and resources issues, looking to the 2020\/2025 horizon: climate mitigation and energy transformations, food security, overfishing; and wildlife trafficking and biodiversity loss.","body":"<p>The environmental challenges of the Atlantic Space are manifold and mutually reinforcing. This paper examines the dynamics of four key environment and resources issues, looking to the 2020\/2025 horizon: climate mitigation and energy transformations; food security; overfishing; and wildlife trafficking and biodiversity loss. Each is global in nature, yet Atlantic actors play influential roles and have shared interests in, and critical resources for, addressing them. Underlying these challenges are regional and global drivers of resource consumption and production. Rising demand for resources to feed growing and wealthier populations is shifting global production and consumption patterns, and in turn, creating heavy environmental strain. Where policy solutions prove insufficient to internalize costs, economic interests will continue to drive unsustainable, and often illegal, resource use and consumption. Nevertheless, despite negative trajectories in many areas, the Atlantic Space offers unique opportunities for concerted action and furthering networks of state and non-state actors to address the environmental challenges of today and of the future through coordinated regional action.<\/p>","views":"251","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2015-09-11 17:08:00","modified":"2016-01-31 22:41:04"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"163","content_id":"1113","type":"1","file_name":"1113-WP9_Ecologic_Patterns of Production and Consumption in the Atlantic Space and Future Environment and Resource Scenarios.pdf","description":"Patterns of Production and Consumption in the Atlantic Space and Future Environment and Resource Scenarios","created":"2015-09-10 17:20:20","modified":"2015-09-10 17:20:20"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"6351","content_id":"1113","tag_id":"26","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"26","code":"resources-and-environment","name":"Resources and environment","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"9AC4AB","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:08:22"}},{"id":"6344","content_id":"1113","tag_id":"162","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"