7 09:57:02"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"1114","code":"political--social-and-cultural-trends","user_id":"1","title":"Political, social and cultural trends","abstract":"&nbsp;In political, social and cultural terms, the Atlantic space is a puzzle. Cooperation in the Atlantic Basin will probably take place &lsquo;&agrave; la carte&rsquo;, rather than on the basis of a clear all-encompassing institutional design. Paper by Susanne Gratius at FRIDE.","body":"<p>In political, social and cultural terms, the Atlantic space is a puzzle. Cooperation in the Atlantic Basin will probably take place &lsquo;<em>&agrave; la carte&rsquo;<\/em>, rather than on the basis of a clear all-encompassing institutional design. Democracy is the prevalent form of government across the Atlantic, but with major regional variations and a predominance of hybrid or authoritarian regimes in Africa. Socio-economic challenges also differ considerably among Atlantic countries. Social inequalities within countries have been growing larger in recent years in both advanced and developing countries. Demography will be a critical factor for the future of the Atlantic, with Africa being the only region where high population growth rates are expected and Europe being the fastest ageing region. Beyond states, the influence of multinational companies, NGOs, social networks, sub-national entities (cities, regions) and migrant communities over government decisions and within multilateral organisations and fora is set to grow. Therefore, future convergence in the Atlantic Basin cannot be planned top-down, but needs to encompass and build on the perspectives and priorities of societal actors, from the bottom up.&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"91","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2015-09-10 17:11:00","modified":"2016-02-06 10:09:48"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"164","content_id":"1114","type":"1","file_name":"1114-WP9_FRIDE_Political, social and cultural trends in the Atlantic.pdf","description":"Political, social and cultural trends in the Atlantic","created":"2015-09-10 17:21:38","modified":"2015-09-10 17:21:38"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"6212","content_id":"1114","tag_id":"25","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"25","code":"people-and-institutions","name":"People and institutions","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"EBC635","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:04:26"}},{"id":"6206","content_id":"1114","tag_id":"85","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"85","code":"culture","name":"Culture","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 10:54:50","modified":"2013-09-27 10:54:50"}},{"id":"6207","content_id":"1114","tag_id":"24","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"24","code":"political-relations","name":"Political relations","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 10:04:54","modified":"2013-09-27 10:04:54"}},{"id":"6208","content_id":"1114","tag_id":"99","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"99","code":"political-systems","name":"Political systems","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 10:58:08","modified":"2013-09-27 10:58:08"}},{"id":"6209","content_id":"1114","tag_id":"272","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"272","code":"development-gap","name":"development gap","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"6210","content_id":"1114","tag_id":"23","order":"5","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"23","code":"social-relations","name":"Social relations","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 10:08:58","modified":"2013-09-27 10:08:58"}},{"id":"6211","content_id":"1114","tag_id":"273","order":"6","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"273","code":"non-governmental-actors","name":"non governmental actors","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"6212","content_id":"1114","tag_id":"25","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"25","code":"people-and-institutions","name":"People and institutions","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"EBC635","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:04:26"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"944","code":"webinar-regionalisms-across-the-atlantic1","user_id":"1","title":"Webinar: Regionalisms across the Atlantic","abstract":"The second Atlantic Future webinar &ldquo;Regionalisms across the Atlantic: divergences and convergences&rdquo; took place on 22 June and was conducted by Dr Frank Mattheis, Senior Researcher at the Centre for the Study of Governance Innovation at the University of Pretoria, and Atlantic Future partner. The webinar was presented by Laia Tarragona, Project Manager at CIDOB, and Elizabeth Tedsen, Senior Resercher at Ecologic Institute moderated the Q&amp;A session.","body":"<p>The prevalence of national and global interactions notwithstanding, regions have established themselves as a crucial space in international relations.&nbsp; In addition, regions are also emerging as actors in their own right. Projects to build regions are particularly active in the four Atlantic regions (Latin America, Africa, Europe and North America) and some of them even transcend the continental divisions. Frank Mattheis spoke of the logics of regional projects, the driving actors and the capacities of regional organisations, and he assessed the different models and trajectories of regionalism on the four shores of the Atlantic space.&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p>The recording of the webinar is available on YouTube: <a href=\"https:\/\/www.youtube.com\/watch?v=oQm5zHJLGfs\">https:\/\/www.youtube.com\/watch?v=oQm5zHJLGfs<\/a><\/p>\r\n<p>The following questions were posted by the audience and answered by the speaker during the webinar:<\/p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>For some stakeholders of the Atlantic, the idea regionalism as it was understood during the 90&rsquo;s has become obsolete to understand regional dynamics and transform regional integration. Do you agree with this statement?<\/li>\r\n<\/ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>In your view, what other forms of regional integration can be boosted in order to integrate new non-state actors that are shaping the inter-regional relations in the Atlantic?<\/li>\r\n<\/ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>During the Atlantic Future research we found that there was an impression that emerging regional blocs in South America and Africa were actually pivoted towards Asia. E.g. Pacific Alliance and Eastern Africa. Would you say that is true?<\/li>\r\n<\/ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>South American countries, such as Brazil emphasize the fact that the South Atlantic dynamics are very different from the North Atlantic. Some of these countries are very skeptic about NATO&rsquo;s presence in their surrounding waters. Considering that, do you envisage any kind of cooperation\/interaction between organizations such as the ZOPACAS and Unasur and NATO in the near future?<\/li>\r\n<\/ul>\r\n<p>This webinar was jointly organised by CIDOB and Ecologic Institute.<\/p>","views":"74","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2015-06-29 10:49:31","modified":"2016-02-05 09:25:56"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[],"ContentTag":[{"id":"5505","content_id":"944","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"5501","content_id":"944","tag_id":"155","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"155","code":"regionalism","name":"Regionalism","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2014-01-10 12:59:30","modified":"2014-01-10 12:59:30"}},{"id":"5502","content_id":"944","tag_id":"141","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"141","code":"latin-america","name":"Latin America","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:43","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:43"}},{"id":"5503","content_id":"944","tag_id":"138","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"138","code":"europe","name":"Europe","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:16:35","modified":"2013-10-25 10:16:35"}},{"id":"5504","content_id":"944","tag_id":"140","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"140","code":"africa","name":"Africa","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:33","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:33"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"5505","content_id":"944","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"904","code":"webinar-regionalisms-across-the-atlantic","user_id":"1","title":"WEBINAR: REGIONALISMS ACROSS THE ATLANTIC","abstract":"ATLANTIC FUTURE is pleased to invite you to a webinar &ldquo;Regionalisms across the Atlantic: divergences and convergences&rdquo;, to be conducted by&nbsp;Frank Mattheis, Senior Researcher at the Centre for the Study of Governance Innovation at the University of Pretoria, and Andr&eacute;s Malamud,Research Fellow at the Institute of Social Sciences (ICS) of the University of Lisbon, as discussant.","body":"<p>The prevalence of national and global interactions notwithstanding, regions have established themselves as a crucial space in international relations.&nbsp; In addition, regions are also emerging as actors in their own right. Projects to build regions are particularly active in the four Atlantic regions (Latin America, Africa, Europe and North America) and some of them even transcend the continental divisions. This Atlantic Future webinar will investigate the logics of regional projects, the driving actors and the capacities of regional organisations. The participants will assess the different models and trajectories of regionalism on the four shores of the Atlantic space. Elizabeth Tedsen at Ecologic Institute will moderate the webinar and Laia Tarragona at CIDOB will present the Atlantic Future project.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Time: 16:00 CET<\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p>The webinar has been scheduled as a&nbsp;Google Hangout on Air. <strong>To view it, follow the link&nbsp;<a href=\"https:\/\/plus.google.com\/events\/cvcikkbrbi7nh3besmuciv8ieng\">https:\/\/plus.google.com\/events\/cvcikkbrbi7nh3besmuciv8ieng<\/a><\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Ask questions:<\/strong>&nbsp;You can post questions prior or during the event. However, note that you need to have a Google+ profile or a Gmail address. Questions will appear on the right side of the screen, which is where you can submit your questions as well. Simply click &ldquo;Ask a new question!&rdquo; and the moderator will see it.&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Requirements:<\/strong>&nbsp;You only need high speed Internet connection (please note that Explorer does not always work. This is why we advise you to use Google Chrome).<\/p>\r\n<p>For more information, please send an e-mail to:&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:ltarragona@cidob.org\">ltarragona@cidob.org<\/a><\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Dr Frank Mattheis<\/strong> is Senior Researcher at the Centre for the Study of Governance Innovation (GovInn) at the University of Pretoria. He joined GovInn in 2014 and is currently carrying out his research on comparative regionalism, interregionalism and maritime security through a postdoc fellowship of the German Academic Exchange Service (DAAD). Prior to GovInn, Frank Mattheis was senior research fellow at the Centre for Area Studies of the University of Leipzig from 2011 to 2014. He is trained in Global Studies with a M.A. from the Universities of Leipzig and Vienna and a Dr. phil. from the University of Leipzig.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Dr Andr&eacute;s Malamud <\/strong>is Research Fellow at the Institute of Social Sciences of the University of Lisboa and Associate Researcher at IPRI. His work has been published in many internationally renowned academic journals. He served four year in the executive committee of the Latin American Political Science Association.<\/p>","views":"647","shares":"0","tweets":"2","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"1","created":"2015-06-12 10:57:00","modified":"2016-02-06 06:52:09"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"crea