ody":"<p>The conferences took place in Hambury (Germany), New Orleanas (USA) and Boston (USA), respectively.<\/p>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/www.giga-hamburg.de\/en\/event\/world-regions-compared-polity-politics-and-policy\">World Regions Compared: Polity, Politics, and Policy\" at the German Institute &nbsp; for &nbsp; Global Affairs, Hamburg<\/a>, February 2015<\/p>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/www.isanet.org\/Conferences\/New-Orleans-2015\">International Studies Association Annual Convention &ldquo;Global IR and Regional Worlds&rdquo;, New Orleans, February 2015<\/a><\/p>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;<a href=\"https:\/\/eustudies.org\/\">European Union Studies Association Biennial Conference &ldquo;The EU After the Crisis: Phoenix or Albatross?&rdquo;, Boston<\/a>, March 2015<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p>Find attached the reports of the three conferences.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"63","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":false,"type":"0","created":"2015-04-21 10:41:00","modified":"2016-01-07 23:09:15"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"127","content_id":"784","type":"1","file_name":"784-Conference report_ World regions compared_ German Political Science Association__ Hamburg February 2015 (3).docx","description":"Conference Report\r\n \u201cWorld Regions Compared\u201d, German Political Science Association, Hamburg, February 2015\r\n","created":"2015-04-21 10:53:05","modified":"2015-04-21 10:53:05"},{"id":"128","content_id":"784","type":"1","file_name":"784-Conference report_ International Studies Association_ 56th Convention_ New Orleans_ USA_ Feb 2015.docx","description":"Conference Report \r\nInternational Studies Association \u2013 56th Convention \u2013 New Orleans, USA\r\n\u201cGlobal IR and Regional Words: A New Agenda for International Studies\u201d\r\n","created":"2015-04-21 10:54:18","modified":"2015-04-21 10:54:18"},{"id":"129","content_id":"784","type":"1","file_name":"784-Conference report_ Biennial Conference of the European Union Studies Association Boston_ March 2015 (2).docx","description":"Conference report, Biennial Conference of the European Union Studies Association, Boston (USA), March 2015","created":"2015-04-21 10:54:51","modified":"2015-04-21 10:54:51"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"5173","content_id":"784","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"5173","content_id":"784","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"763","code":"webinar-ttip-and-the-wider-atlantic-1","user_id":"1","title":"WEBINAR: TTIP AND THE WIDER ATLANTIC ","abstract":"The first Atlantic Future webinar explored&nbsp;the potential impact of the TTIP on the four shores of the wider Atlantic Space.","body":"<p>The first Atlantic Future webinar on &ldquo;TTIP and the Wider Atlantic&rdquo; took place on 15 April. Dan Hamilton, Director of the Center for Transatlantic Relations at SAIS at Johns Hopkins University, and Atlantic Future partner, explored the potential impact of the TTIP on the four shores of the wider Atlantic Space and elaborated on how the US and EU should engage other countries. Tim Ridout, Wider Atlantic fellow at the German Marshall Fund of the United States, also Atlantic Future partner, served as discussant, tackled some of the concerns that exist on the TTIP and explored the perceptions that other countries have on the TTIP.<\/p>\r\n<p>The video is available on YouTube: <a href=\"https:\/\/www.youtube.com\/watch?v=EP7M8j3P55I\">https:\/\/www.youtube.com\/watch?v=EP7M8j3P55I<\/a><\/p>\r\n<p>The following questions were posted by the audience and answered by the speakers during the webinar:<\/p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Do you think that WTO should concentrate in rules convergence and dispute settlement and leave gods and services market access to bilateral agreements?<\/li>\r\n<li>If the TTIP finally is achieved, what would be the consequences for the WTO role and the negotiations of the Doha Round future?<\/li>\r\n<li>The TTIP is contested for a lack of transparency and the doubts on its benefits for societies. Are these benefits equally distributed in the USA and the EU? How to reduce the reluctance of citizens towards the Treaty and increase transparency?<\/li>\r\n<li>What can the TTIP mean for the construction of the Atlantic space? Can the TTIP constitute a response to the increasing Chinese influence in the wider Atlantic?<\/li>\r\n<li>Is there not a risk that countries in the South Atlantic feel left out and turn to other partners such as China? How should countries in the South be approached or engaged to avoid this?<\/li>\r\n<li>The single undertaking system of negotiation in the WTO makes achieving results in some acceptable and divisible packages very complicated. Is the TTIP a fast track Atlantic solution for the world to skip the WTO Round obstacles?<\/li>\r\n<\/ul>\r\n<p>This webinar was jointly organised by CIDOB and Ecologic Institute.<\/p>","views":"519","shares":"0","tweets":"2","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2015-04-20 10:38:00","modified":"2016-02-06 00:33:11"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"123","content_id":"763","type":"1","file_name":"763-Webinar TTIP.pdf","description":"","created":"2015-04-20 11:40:00","modified":"2015-04-20 11:40:00"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"5169","content_id":"763","tag_id":"20","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"20","code":"economy-and-finance","name":"Economy and finance","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"A85CA0","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-09-27 09:57:02"}},{"id":"5163","content_id":"763","tag_id":"186","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"186","code":"ttip","name":"ttip","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"5164","content_id":"763","tag_id":"15","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"15","code":"south-atlantic","name":"South Atlantic","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 11:29:49","modified":"2013-09-27 11:29:49"}},{"id":"5165","content_id":"763","tag_id":"202","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"202","code":"wto","name":"wto","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"5166","content_id":"763","tag_id":"125","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"125","code":"johns-hopkins-university-jhu","name":"Johns Hopkins University (JHU)","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-30 10:19:12","modified":"2013-09-30 10:19:12"}},{"id":"5167","content_id":"763","tag_id":"157","order":"5","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"157","code":"german-marshall-fund","name":"german marshall fund","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"5168","content_id":"763","tag_id":"88","order":"6","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"88","code":"governance","name":"Governance","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 10:55:35","modified":"2013-09-27 10:55:35"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"5169","content_id":"763","tag_id":"20","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"20","code":"economy-and-finance","name":"Economy and finance","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"A85CA0","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-09-27 09:57:02"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"481","code":"atlantic-voices--1-with-jordi-vaquer","user_id":"1","title":"Atlantic Voices # 1 with Jordi Vaquer","abstract":"Discover the meaning of the Atlantic Space for the Atlantic Future project. An interview with Jordi Vaquer i Fan&eacute;s, Director of the Open Society Initiative for Europe and Associate Senior Researcher of CIDOB.","body":"<p><em>Jordi Vaquer is the director of the Open Society Initiative for Europe and the regional director for Europe at the Open Society Foundations. In these positions, he works to advance the values and institutions of open society in the cities and countries of the European Union and the Western Balkans. Vaquer writes and provides commentary for Spanish media, and often speaks at international debates and seminars on international affairs and EU politics. Before becoming director of the Open Society Initiative for Europe, Vaquer was director of the Barcelona Centre for International Affairs, one of southern Europe&rsquo;s most influential international relations think tanks and Coordinator of the Atlantic Future project. Vaquer graduated from the Autonomous University of Barcelona, Spain; received an MA from the College of Europe in Bruges, Belgium; and completed a PhD in international relations at the London School of Economics and Political Science.<\/em><\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Q: What does the ATLANTIC FUTURE project refer to with the expression &lsquo;Atlantic Space&rsquo;? Why should we think about the Atlantic in those terms?<\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p>A:&nbsp; The research focus of the Atlantic Future project is not self-evident. The Atlantic is an ocean, not an integrated region in any re&shy;cognizable shape; and it is not where the fo&shy;cus of international relations is, by contrast with the Arctic, the Indian Ocean and, above all, the Pacific. And yet, the space where Afri&shy;ca, the Americas and Europe meet remains one of crucial importance for Global Gover&shy;nance. The Atlantic perhaps exemplifies North\/South dynamics better than any other macro-region. It contains many of the difficulties and challenges of Global Governance; but, to address them, it can build on historical, cultural, linguistic and ideological links that cannot be compa&shy;red to those in any other Ocean basin. The weight of its past is an obstacle, but can also serve as a launching pad for future cooperation. And all Atlantic powers (from the US, the EU and Brazil, to the small littoral states of West Africa and the Caribbean) have an interest in not seeing the Atlantic become a backwater of global trade, and in maximizing the hitherto overlooked potential of their Atlantic links. These are all good reasons to take a serious, in depth look at the Atlantic space as an interlinked whole.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;To think about an Atlantic space is neither an exercise in wishful thinking, nor a nor&shy;mative endeavour. Atlantic Future as an intellectual project is an invi&shy;tation to lateral thinking and unusual re&shy;search, to take the less beaten track and ask the unexpected questions, to highlight the almost invisible connections and interpret the emerging trends. The research is teaching us about the four continents that border it, and about their links; at the same time, we are learning about Globalization, and the results may point towards possible roads to better global governance.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Q: Which do you consider to be the trends that could shape the emergence of an Atlantic Space?<\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p>A: The global redistribution of power affects the Atlantic space as much as any other part of the World. The emergence of the South holds the promise of a radical re-equilibrium for the whole Atlantic, with new opportunities for growth and exchange in all directions and, potentially, plenty of space for win-win situations. The pivot of the gravity centre of global geoeconomics towards Asia, on the contrary, represents a challenge to a space that was, for a long time, at the centre of Globalisation. Another trend is the emergence of new forms of regionalism in Africa and Latin America, less shaped by the EU model, and in a context where countries are rapidly abandoning old, post-colonial dependency relationships and developing multi-vector strategies (towards North America and Europe, but also towards East Asia, South Asia, inside the regions themselves, and across the southern Atlantic).<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Q: Which areas for potential regional cooperation do you envisage for the Atlantic?<\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p>A: &nbsp;The three areas with most potential for cooperation that I see are security, food production and environmental governance. In the area of security, the Atlantic space has a number of grey spaces &ndash; whether it is fragile states like Haiti and Guinea Bissau, weak states like Mauritania and Honduras that struggle to control violent groups, or even black holes of insecurity inside relatively large and powerful countries such as Mexico and Nigeria &ndash; where different kinds of mostly unconventional security risks (terrorism, drug traffic, violent crime and piracy) flourish. In food production, the Atlantic regions combined (the Americas, Africa and Europe) hold the key to addressing food security at global scale, but they have to find the ways to do it without intolerable ecologic impact. Finally, environmental governance is an urgent issue that cannot be delayed. From the preservation of fisheries to climate change, from biodiversity to chemical pollution of the oceans, the Atlantic could pioneer the solutions to a range of environmental issues.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"154","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"1","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2015-03-13 12:12:00","modified":"2016-02-07 19:01:30"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"116","content_id":"481","type":"1","file_name":"481-ATLANTIC VOICES_01.pdf","description":"Atlantic Voices. Jordi Vaquer.","created":"2015-03-13 12:21:26","modified":"2015-03-13 12:21:26"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"5063","content_id":"481","tag_id":"245","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"245","code":"atlantic-voices","name":"atlantic voices","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"5067","content_id":"481","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"5061","content_id":"481","tag_id":"5","order":"1","created"