"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"4398","content_id":"337","tag_id":"26","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"26","code":"resources-and-environment","name":"Resources and environment","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"9AC4AB","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:08:22"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"336","code":"marine-resources-and-coastal-livelihoods","user_id":"1","title":"Marine resources and coastal livelihoods","abstract":"ATLANTIC FUTURE scientific paper no. 15 is out: \"Marine resource management and coastal livelihoods: an Atlantic perspective\", by Elizabeth Tedsen, Benjamin Boteler, Katriona McGlade, Tanja&nbsp;Srebotnjak, and Katrina Abhold at&nbsp;Ecologic Institute","body":"<p>Marine ecosystem resources play important roles in coastal countries, providing numerous benefits and services. This paper examines opportunities and challenges to managing marine resources, promoting coastal protection, and supporting coastal livelihoods for select Atlantic Basin coastal countries. Through in-depth case study analyses of four Atlantic Basin countries &ndash;&nbsp;Canada, Guatemala, Guinea-Bissau, and Venezuela &ndash; we explore the relative importance of marine resources, management measures, challenges and trade-offs, and opportunities for improving marine management and sustainable resource use. The case studies highlight the great environmental, socioeconomic, and political diversity found throughout the Atlantic Basin. At the same time, common challenges and opportunities for marine resource use and management within these countries and across the wider Atlantic can be identified, revealing the need for the strong regional cooperation to promote sustainability, protect marine resources and coastal areas, and maximize benefits for coastal populations.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Download the paper here:<\/strong>&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"628","shares":"0","tweets":"1","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2014-09-29 15:00:00","modified":"2016-02-04 22:37:16"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"91","content_id":"336","type":"1","file_name":"336-ATLANTIC FUTURE_15_Marine resources.compressed.pdf","description":"Scientific paper no. 15: \"Marine resource management and coastal livelihoods: an Atlantic perspective\"","created":"2014-10-09 10:10:20","modified":"2014-10-09 10:10:20"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"4452","content_id":"336","tag_id":"26","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"26","code":"resources-and-environment","name":"Resources and environment","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"9AC4AB","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:08:22"}},{"id":"4445","content_id":"336","tag_id":"162","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"162","code":"resources","name":"resources","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"4446","content_id":"336","tag_id":"117","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"117","code":"sustainability","name":"Sustainability","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 11:14:55","modified":"2013-09-27 11:14:55"}},{"id":"4447","content_id":"336","tag_id":"126","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"126","code":"cooperation","name":"Cooperation","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-30 10:21:56","modified":"2013-09-30 10:21:56"}},{"id":"4448","content_id":"336","tag_id":"231","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"231","code":"ecosystem","name":"ecosystem","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"4449","content_id":"336","tag_id":"235","order":"5","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"235","code":"resource-management","name":"resource management","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"4450","content_id":"336","tag_id":"233","order":"6","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"233","code":"coastal-protection","name":"coastal protection","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"4451","content_id":"336","tag_id":"150","order":"7","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"4452","content_id":"336","tag_id":"26","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"26","code":"resources-and-environment","name":"Resources and environment","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"9AC4AB","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:08:22"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"332","code":"the-role-of-language-in-the-atlantic","user_id":"1","title":"The role of language in the Atlantic","abstract":"[Photo credit: Anthony Hevron]\r\n&nbsp;\r\nATLANTIC FUTURE scientific paper no. 14 is out: \"The community of Portuguese Language Speaking Countries: The role of language in a globalizing world\", by Edalina Rodrigues Sanches at&nbsp;IPRI-UNL","body":"<p>Building on Joseph Nye&rsquo;s concept of soft power, this paper conducts a case study analysis on the role and relevance of language in the Community of Portuguese Language Speaking Countries (CPLP). This organization was built on the shared history and language of its eight member states &ndash; Angola, Brazil, Cape Verde, Guinea-Bissau, Mozambique, Portugal, Sao&nbsp;Tome and Principe and Timor-Leste &ndash; and has recently attracted the interest of many states in and out of the Atlantic Basin. In this context, language is one of the assets allowing this organization to increase its international projection and attractiveness. Notwithstanding, it is also true that recent power configurations in the South Atlantic &ndash; with energy and security matters&nbsp;at its core &ndash; has also contributed to increasing the CPLP&rsquo;s &lsquo;magnetism&rsquo;. Hence, we argue that language has allowed the CPLP to project soft power (through the pivotal role played by the governments of Portugal and Brazil), but that language itself has in turn benefited from the economic attractiveness of the organization. Many states in and out of the Atlantic Basin now perceive the CPLP as a relevant forum through which they can reach the &lsquo;Lusophone world&rsquo;. In as much as entering the CPLP requires compliance with certain political values and the adoption of the Portuguese language (or of policies that promote its diffusion) there is a new opportunity to increase language potential.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Download the paper here:<\/strong>&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"312","shares":"0","tweets":"2","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2014-09-29 14:04:00","modified":"2016-02-06 14:15:22"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145