.<\/p>\r\n<p>The workshop will be an excellent opportunity to disseminate results of the Project and to hold discussions with eminent experts on the future of the Atlantic.<\/p>\r\n<p>This event is&nbsp;<strong>by invitation only<\/strong>.<\/p>","views":"94","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":false,"type":"1","created":"2014-04-24 14:51:00","modified":"2015-11-30 00:48:24"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":"86","datetime":"2014-06-06 09:00:00","country":"South Africa","city":"Pretoria","address":"","map":""},"Resource":[{"id":"53","content_id":"86","type":"1","file_name":"86-Governance Innovation Week_Programme.pdf","description":"","created":"2014-06-12 12:28:10","modified":"2014-06-12 12:28:10"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"2913","content_id":"86","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"2908","content_id":"86","tag_id":"36","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"36","code":"events","name":"Events","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"995B31","created":"2013-09-27 09:58:37","modified":"2013-09-27 09:58:37"}},{"id":"2909","content_id":"86","tag_id":"178","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"178","code":"university-of-pretoria","name":"University of Pretoria","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2014-04-24 14:52:42","modified":"2014-04-24 14:52:42"}},{"id":"2910","content_id":"86","tag_id":"179","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"179","code":"south-africa","name":"South Africa","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2014-04-24 14:53:06","modified":"2014-04-24 14:53:06"}},{"id":"2911","content_id":"86","tag_id":"180","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"180","code":"pretoria","name":"Pretoria","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2014-04-24 14:56:21","modified":"2014-04-24 14:56:21"}},{"id":"2912","content_id":"86","tag_id":"5","order":"5","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"5","code":"atlantic-space","name":"Atlantic space","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 09:55:08","modified":"2013-09-27 09:55:08"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"2913","content_id":"86","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"54","code":"seminar-for-young-researchers-in-mexico","user_id":"1","title":"SEMINAR FOR YOUNG RESEARCHERS IN MEXICO","abstract":"On 21 February 2014, CIDE organised a seminar with students of International Relations with an interest in the subject of Atlantic. More than 50 students attended the seminar. Several senior ATLANTIC FUTURE researchers participated in the seminar: R. Andreas Kraemer at Ecologic Institute (Germany), Alfredo Valladao at HEM (Morocco), Paul Isbell at Johns Hopkins University (United States) and Mark Aspinwall at CIDE (Mexico). Lorena Ruano at CIDE (Mexico) acted as the moderator.","body":"<p>Lorena Ruano (CIDE) presented the ATLANTIC FUTURE project to the students, highlighting its main features. Next, Alfredo Valladao (HEM) spoke about the strengths of the Atlantic. While everybody talks about the Pacific and the emergence of China, he expressed to be sceptical about that. It is the Atlantic century we are going to see coming up, he noted, and not only the North Atlantic but the South Atlantic too. He made the following points: <strong>the new reserves of energy are in the Atlantic, and energy is the core of development and economic life.<\/strong> There is a huge basin of energy that can put us together and make the Atlantic one of the centres of energy producing of the world. Furthermore, North America and South America are the biggest food producers in the world. Africa and Latin America still have a huge stock of free land and water. There are environmental problems, he conceded, but <strong>we can see the Atlantic as a bread basket for the world<\/strong>. That is a huge area where we can have good cooperation. Thirdly, <strong>the Atlantic is home to huge consumer markets<\/strong>. The US alone represents about 1\/3 of the final private consumer, while China only accounts for 4-5% of the world&rsquo;s private consumption. In a world where consumption leads production, the Atlantic will play an enormous role of consumer market for the world&rsquo;s production. Some countries in Africa are developing fast, which will be a huge opportunity for business, cross-interests, production, consumers, etc. But more important, we are living today a real industrial revolution: from the old model of production chains of mass production for mass consumption to new model: that of ICT tech, 3D printing, advanced robotics, etc. That will be very difficult to replicate in some countries in Asia like China, while in the Atlantic there are a lot of possibilities to do that, where societies open enough to be part of this ICT, to be part of it and take advantage of it. Atlantic will probably be the core of the new revolution of the world. Future economic production and consumption will be more centred in the Atlantic.&nbsp; He clarified, though, that this does not mean that it has to be against the Pacific.<\/p>\r\n<p>Paul Isbell (JHU) added that the <strong>Atlantic<\/strong><strong> is a new unit of analysis as well as a tool for new forms of international collaboration<\/strong>. Coming from a view of the Pacific rise, energy dependence to the Middle East, and the rise of the global South, he explained how when drawing an energy map, it revealed that most mental maps that had to do with the Atlantic and energy were either incorrect or beginning to change dramatically. There is a boom in Atlantic energy resources, reserves, in production, shale revolution, the rising role of gas, and other related forms of energy. The Atlantic is almost self-sufficient in energy. <strong>The energy story is really an Atlantic one<\/strong>, he concluded.<\/p>\r\n<p>Mark Aspinwall (CIDE) added how colonisation had a profound effect in linking together Europe, Africa and the Americas. <strong>The Atlantic is a coherent and fundamentally linked area, where there are important flows in terms of values and ideas<\/strong>. The whole idea of international collaboration and international rules is an Atlantic idea and continue to be generated in the Atlantic in an important way. In terms of economics, there has been a huge increase in services, trade and investment in the Atlantic. In terms of security, continued Lorena Ruano (CIDE), NATO is the main military alliance we have today with the most important capacity in terms of military gear and coordination. But one cannot forget that when thinking about the Atlantic, we mostly think of the North Atlantic. The most important economic exchanges happen in the North Atlantic. <strong>The North Atlantic is still dominant but the fastest rising links are in the South Atlantic<\/strong>, especially between Brazil and Africa. The South Atlantic, she concluded, is coming into the picture very fast.<\/p>\r\n<p>In R. Andreas Kraemer&rsquo;s view (Ecologic Institute), the Atlantic story remains strong. Something very important to consider is <strong>the role of China in the Atlantic<\/strong> today. He also made the point that energy systems, all technology providers, all big companies, are Atlantic, which is very disruptive for the environment. But <strong>there is also a problem of solving capacity<\/strong>. In natural resources there is also disruption (with overfishing, destroyed ecosystems, etc.)&nbsp;&nbsp; But if we try to find the best practices, we find them in the North East Atlantic. We can look at them and apply them in other places.<\/p>\r\n<p>Alfredo Valladao (HEM) pointed at one specific problem: there are many challenges. In terms of civil society, things are going quite well: <strong>there is a huge interchange of values, ideas, and people in the Atlantic<\/strong>. And because there is a lot of freedom of travelling and information, the Atlantic is the cradle of cosmopolitan society. In the business sphere, there are a lot of things going on, services and investment, lot of cross investment in countries in the Atlantic. The real challenge is institutionalizing the dialogue, because of bad perceptions. <strong>The Atlantic probably is the space with more regional integration schemes<\/strong>. Brazil is the &ldquo;big guy&rdquo; in the South Atlantic. While it still sees the South Atlantic as its own, it does not have the capabilities to manage it. It is very important to have a real dialogue with Brazil. And Africa is also key. Finally, he referred to the potential for new form of collaboration. Instead of trying to make big schemes, we should concentrate in solving concrete and specific problems together, such as drug trafficking. To sum up, we should look at solvable problems that are Atlantic.<\/p>\r\n<p>An interesting debate with the students ensued. Questions such as the role of Mexico in the Atlantic, what were the effects of being a dual basin country, or the level of institutionalism in the Atlantic were only a few of them.<\/p>\r\n<p>Check photos of the Seminar for Young Researchers below:<\/p>\r\n<p class=\"tab-image-container\">&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p class=\"tab-image-container\"><img class=\"tab-image\" src=\"..\/..\/..\/..\/images\/contents\/54-1395739895.jpg\" alt=\"\" \/>&nbsp; &nbsp;<img class=\"tab-image\" style=\"font-family: 'Open Sans', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 21.920000076293945px;\" src=\"..\/..\/..\/..\/images\/contents\/54-1395740829.jpg\" alt=\"\" \/><\/p>\r\n<p class=\"tab-image-container\"><img class=\"tab-image\" src=\"..\/..\/..\/..\/images\/contents\/54-1395740339.jpg\" alt=\"\" \/>&nbsp; &nbsp;<img class=\"tab-image\" src=\"..\/..\/..\/..\/images\/contents\/54-1395741703.jpg\" alt=\"\" \/><\/p>\r\n<p class=\"tab-image-container\"><img class=\"tab-image\" src=\"..\/..\/..\/..\/images\/contents\/54-1395741302.jpg\" alt=\"\" \/>&nbsp;&nbsp;<img class=\"tab-image\" src=\"..\/..\/..\/..\/images\/contents\/54-1395742732.jpg\" alt=\"\" \/><\/p>","views":"266","shares":"0","tweets":"1","mails":"2","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2014-03-24 14:54:00","modified":"2016-02-01 20:22:23"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[],"ContentTag":[{"id":"2694","content_id":"54","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"2675","content_id":"54","tag_id":"153","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"153","code":"