or":"995B31","created":"2013-09-27 09:58:37","modified":"2013-09-27 09:58:37"}},{"id":"2225","content_id":"33","tag_id":"47","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"47","code":"rabat","name":"Rabat","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 10:05:34","modified":"2013-09-27 10:05:34"}},{"id":"2226","content_id":"33","tag_id":"128","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"128","code":"morocco","name":"Morocco","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-10 11:35:40","modified":"2013-10-10 11:35:40"}},{"id":"2227","content_id":"33","tag_id":"136","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"136","code":"scientific-and-advisory-panel","name":"Scientific and advisory panel","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 11:43:07","modified":"2013-10-25 11:43:07"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"2228","content_id":"33","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"4","code":"transformation-in-the-south-atlantic-","user_id":"1","title":"Transformation in the South Atlantic ","abstract":"The South Atlantic space has in the last decade won greater economic and political autonomy form the US and Europe. Trade and investment have been growing fast in the South-South Atlantic relationship, and the regions of the South are also witnessing a reconfiguration in political influence.","body":"<p>The South Atlantic space has in the last decade won greater economic and political autonomy from the US and Europe. The dynamic Asian markets have driven the economic growth of major South American countries (such as Brazil, Argentina, Chile or Peru), most notably in the sector of commodities, both non-renewable (such as mineral and fossil fuels) and renewable (such as agricultural products). Asian, mainly Chinese, products have been flooding markets across the region. An even more dramatic shift has taken place in Africa, where the search for commodities has attracted unprecedented levels of Chinese investment, and has fuelled economic growth and further investment from other non-traditional sources such as the Gulf States, India, Malaysia or Brazil.<\/p>\r\n<p>Trade and investment in the South-South Atlantic have been growing fast, both within the Atlantic space and between the Atlantic and extra-Atlantic partners. Trade between Brazil and Africa has increased six fold between 2000 and 2011 (from US$4.2 billion to US$27.6 billion), and Brazil is the third largest trade partner of Africa as a whole, after China and India. Oil-producing Nigeria and Angola account for almost 50% of these trade flows. At the same time, China-Africa trade, driven by commodities, has grown more than ten-fold over the last decade, doubling in nominal terms every three years. The share of Brazil&rsquo;s trade with the other BRICs jumped from 9% to 17% in the space of only three years, from 2006 to 2009. The old, largely rhetoric South-South cooperation has evolved into a complex relationship which involves a growing number of actors with different objectives; among them are transnational corporations and powerful lobbies but also cities, language communities or diasporas.<\/p>\r\n<p>The regions of the South are also witnessing a reconfiguration in political influence. North Atlantic powers are losing ground, thus allowing non-Atlantic actors to seek new influence and regional actors to emerge. In Sub-Saharan Africa, political investment by South Africa and other regional players in the African Union and sub-regional organizations is paralleled by a creeping &lsquo;multipolarisation&rsquo; of continental politics. In particular, South Africa and Nigeria aim to consolidate their role as regional leaders and important interlocutors for third partners beyond Africa. Together with Brazil and India, South Africa has launched the IBSA format for political dialogue and economic cooperation, has invested in the BASIC (Brazil, South Africa, India and China) platform on climate change negotiations and joined the BRICS in 2011. At the same time, it has developed a strategic partnership with the EU, with the latter seeking to strike a new balance between bilateral and inter-regional engagement both in Africa and in South America. Nigeria is seeking political benefits from its pivotal role in energy flows, accounting for 11% of US oil imports, 16% of South Africa&rsquo;s and 8% of India&rsquo;s.<\/p>\r\n<p>North Africa, long time stagnant at the political and economic level, is at the heart of changes that are shaking the Arab world and transforming its political and social landscape. The problems that still trouble the region &ndash; youth unemployment, gender inequality, lack of competitiveness and dismal research and innovation rates &ndash; could be overcome faster than expected if the current transformation liberates new creative energies in all fields, from economy to social structures. North Africa is moving beyond its dependency on Europe and slowly globalizing its international partners, searching for new opportunities in Asia, Africa, Latin America and the Gulf.<\/p>\r\n<p>In South America, Brazil&rsquo;s external projection is manifest in its solid regional engagement and good cooperation with its neighbours. Brazil, as a leading investor in South America, has sought to deliver new impulse to MERCOSUR (Common Southern Market) and is providing political impetus to regional cooperation through new formats such as UNASUR (Union of South American Nations) and the CELAC (Community of Latin American and Caribbean States). Also thanks to such initiatives, cooperation and integration processes have acquired new dynamism in South America. A shift has been taking place from mainly liberalisation-based economic integration towards a more physical and political agenda that includes asymmetries, complementarities and dispute resolution forums. Against this backdrop, the US and the EU have reached out to Brazil to establish and develop bilateral strategic partnerships.<\/p>","views":"523","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"2","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2013-07-24 18:26:00","modified":"2016-02-05 16:17:48"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[],"ContentTag":[{"id":"1467","content_id":"4","tag_id":"20","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"20","code":"economy-and-finance","name":"Economy and finance","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"A85CA0","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-09-27 09:57:02"}},{"id":"1455","content_id":"4","tag_id":"15","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"15","code":"south-atlantic","name":"South Atlantic","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 11:29:49","modified":"2013-09-27 11:29:49"}},{"id":"1456","content_id":"4","tag_id":"16","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"16","code":"trade","name":"Trade","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 10:26:12","modified":"2013-09-27 10:26:12"}},{"id":"1457","content_id":"4","tag_id":"74","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"74","code":"markets","name":"Ma