ive (ABI) of the Center for Transatlantic Relations (CTR) at Johns Hopkins University SAIS jointly convened&nbsp;a seminar&nbsp;on \"Climate change in the Atlantic Basin\" in April 2013. Daniel Hamilton and&nbsp;R. Andreas Kraemer&nbsp;presented the project ATLANTIC FUTURE to a wide audience in Washington DC, United States, and expert panelists presented on the Atlantic&ndash;specific aspects of climate change impacts, challenges, and governance and engaged in roundtable discussions with the audience.<\/p>\r\n<p>Check the videos of the seminar here:&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/www.youtube.com\/watch?v=0gEdsqyM_Z4&amp;feature=youtu.be\">Panel 1<\/a><\/p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/www.youtube.com\/watch?v=XSm9i83YN_s&amp;feature=youtu.be\">Panel 2<\/a><\/p>\r\n<p>A&nbsp;short summary of the event and details of&nbsp;participants&nbsp;can be&nbsp;found at the <a href=\"http:\/\/www.ecologic.eu\/8680\">website<\/a> of Ecologic Institute.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"163","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"1","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2013-05-03 00:28:00","modified":"2015-12-11 11:51:06"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[],"ContentTag":[{"id":"855","content_id":"29","tag_id":"26","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"26","code":"resources-and-environment","name":"Resources and environment","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"9AC4AB","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:08:22"}},{"id":"849","content_id":"29","tag_id":"107","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"107","code":"climate-change","name":"Climate change","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 11:04:29","modified":"2013-09-27 11:04:29"}},{"id":"850","content_id":"29","tag_id":"1","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"1","code":"atlantic-basin","name":"Atlantic Basin","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 09:54:32","modified":"2013-09-27 09:54:32"}},{"id":"851","content_id":"29","tag_id":"36","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"36","code":"events","name":"Events","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"995B31","created":"2013-09-27 09:58:37","modified":"2013-09-27 09:58:37"}},{"id":"852","content_id":"29","tag_id":"124","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"124","code":"ecologic-institute-gmbh-ecologic","name":"Ecologic Institute GmbH (ECOLOGIC)","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-02 14:28:09","modified":"2013-12-02 14:28:09"}},{"id":"853","content_id":"29","tag_id":"125","order":"5","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"125","code":"johns-hopkins-university-jhu","name":"Johns Hopkins University (JHU)","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-30 10:19:12","modified":"2013-09-30 10:19:12"}},{"id":"854","content_id":"29","tag_id":"126","order":"6","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"126","code":"cooperation","name":"Cooperation","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-30 10:21:56","modified":"2013-09-30 10:21:56"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"855","content_id":"29","tag_id":"26","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"26","code":"resources-and-environment","name":"Resources and environment","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"9AC4AB","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:08:22"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"25","code":"a-global-order-in-evolution","user_id":"1","title":"A global order in evolution","abstract":"The international order, as established at the end of World War II, has changed beyond recognition over the last two decades, and a redistribution of power is currently reshaping the international system. A global order in evolution contextualises the research of ATLANTIC FUTURE.","body":"<p>The international order, as established at the end of World War II, has changed beyond recognition over the last two decades. The triumph of the North Atlantic powers in the Cold War slowly started to give way to <strong>a redistribution of power in all its dimensions<\/strong> (hard and soft, political and economic), which currently is the predominant trend reshaping the international system. It includes both <strong>power shifts among state actors, most notably towards Asia, and the diffusion of power away from states to a variety of non-state actors.<\/strong> However, that power transition does not seem to lead to a succession of US pre-eminence. On the one hand, the material resources of the US remain unparalleled across most dimensions of power, although the economic crisis is seriously affecting the country&rsquo;s profile on the international stage. On the other hand, no individual country, or group of countries, seems able to replace the US in its traditional role of milieu-shaping and provision of global public goods for the foreseeable future. Reforming multilateral frameworks, therefore, is going to be critical to ensure openness and stability of a polycentric international system. Creation of new formats such as the G20 and a progressive transformation of existing institutions, such as the IMF, are part of the adjustment to the new realities. A more open multilateralism is emerging with the diversification of the multilateral playing fields and the emergence of new actors in multilateralism other than states.<\/p>\r\n<p>A general shift of power away from the Northern Atlantic towards the Pacific, or even the Asian heartland, is a defining feature of contemporary international relations, particularly in terms of economic dynamism. The centre of growth is situated in Asia, with China as a major player. Latin America, with Brazilian leadership, and more recently also Africa are playing a growing role on the international stage.<strong> This shift of power towards the Global South is rebalancing relations around and within the Atlantic space<\/strong>. Until recently the North America-Europe transatlantic link was overwhelmingly predominant in the region. North-South relations between the USA and Latin America and Europe and Africa have suffered from a profound asymmetry. However, slowly the space is opening up and multiple levels of engagement are developing across the Atlantic space and with partners in other regions. Regional formats and bilateral partnerships are redrawing the political map of the Atlantic, including a proliferation of South-South links as well as triangulations between advanced, middle income and developing partners (e.g. the trilateral alliance between Brazil, South Africa and India or the BRICS). Large emerging powers such as Brazil reach out to Africa and aim to play a bigger role on global issues in multilateral and mini-lateral fora.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"158","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"1","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2013-05-02 10:45:00","modified":"2016-02-08 04:47:37"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[],"ContentTag":[{"id":"7151","cont