false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:25","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:25"}},{"id":"7145","content_id":"25","tag_id":"141","order":"7","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"141","code":"latin-america","name":"Latin America","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:43","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:43"}},{"id":"7146","content_id":"25","tag_id":"140","order":"8","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"140","code":"africa","name":"Africa","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:33","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:33"}},{"id":"7147","content_id":"25","tag_id":"4","order":"9","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"4","code":"global-south","name":"Global South","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 09:58:55","modified":"2013-09-27 09:58:55"}},{"id":"7148","content_id":"25","tag_id":"5","order":"10","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"5","code":"atlantic-space","name":"Atlantic space","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 09:55:08","modified":"2013-09-27 09:55:08"}},{"id":"7149","content_id":"25","tag_id":"138","order":"11","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"138","code":"europe","name":"Europe","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:16:35","modified":"2013-10-25 10:16:35"}},{"id":"7150","content_id":"25","tag_id":"147","order":"12","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"147","code":"international-relations","name":"international relations","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-11-18 11:32:59","modified":"2013-11-18 11:32:59"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"7151","content_id":"25","tag_id":"20","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"20","code":"economy-and-finance","name":"Economy and finance","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"A85CA0","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-09-27 09:57:02"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"3","code":"the-atlantic-in-an-interpolar-world","user_id":"1","title":"The Atlantic in an interpolar world","abstract":"The redistribution of power is perhaps the predominant trend reshaping the international system. Different authors have offered different readings and conceptualisations of the erosion of American and Western predominance coining concepts such as multipolar world, a post-American world or a non-polar world. ATLANTIC FUTURE adopts a distinct position.","body":"<p>ATLANTIC FUTURE adopts the concept of interpolarity, coined by the researcher Giovanni Grevi. It is ATLANTIC FUTURE&rsquo;s assumption that we live in an interpolar world, where multipolarity and interdependence are equally important. On the one hand, by rescuing polarity we are able to defend the central role of the state, which allows, among other things, to account for the rise of China, Brazil and other emerging state powers. On the other hand, interdependence captures the links not only among states but also among non-state actors, and stresses the increasing interconnectedness among international actors and issues and technological advance and the diffusion of power.<\/p>\r\n<p>The Atlantic, the space where American and, before that, European pre-eminence was most evident in the past, is changing fast, and its study can yield useful insights into how interpolarity works in practice. When looking at relations between large and middle powers, sheer balance of power paradigms fit international politics in the Atlantic space less than the more nuanced concept of interpolarity. The latter does not exclude or neglect competition or hard geopolitical considerations, but sets them in the broader framework of interdependence. This is all the more relevant in a context such as the Atlantic where relations between the main state actors are predominantly not defined in antagonistic terms and trans-national threats are largely common ones. An interpolar system is interest-based, problem driven and process-oriented. Focusing on interests does not mean emphasising ruthless self-interest only but also exploring the scope for the convergence of national interests, and relevant incentives. Numerous challenges across the Atlantic require cooperative solutions and awareness of such imperative across different regions, while arguably growing, needs scrutiny. For example, organised crime or climate change affect different countries in different ways.<\/p>","views":"274","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"2","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2013-05-01 16:24:00","modified":"2016-02-05 22:12:22"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[],"ContentTag":[{"id":"1439","content_id":"3","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"1428","content_id":"3","tag_id":"123","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"123","code":"international-balance-of-power","name":"International balance of power","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-30 09:50:08","modified":"2013-09-30 09:50:08"}},{"id":"1429","content_id":"3","tag_id":"121","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"121","code":"interdependence","name":"Interdependence","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 13:12:07","modified":"2013-09-27 13:12:07"}},{"id":"1430","content_id":"3","tag_id":"11","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"11","code":"multipolarity","name":"Multipolarity","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 10:04:11","modified":"2013-09-27 10:04:11"}},{"id":"1431","content_id":"3","tag_id":"42","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"42","code":"brics","name":"BRICS","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 09:56:17","modified":"2013-09-27 09:56:17"}},{"id":"1432","content_id":"3","tag_id":"5","order":"5","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"5","code":"atlantic-space","name":"Atlantic space","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 09:55:08","modified":"2013-09-27 09:55:08"}},{"id":"1433","content_id":"3","tag_id":"138","order":"6","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"138","code":"europe","name":"Europe","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:16:35","modified":"2013-10-25 10:16:35"}},{"id":"1434","content_id":"3","tag_id":"7","order":"7","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"7","code":"power","name":"Power","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 10:05:06","modified":"2013-09-27 10:05:06"}},{"id":"1435","content_id":"3","tag_id":"41","order":"8","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"41","code":"actors","name":"Actors","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 09:53:51","modified":"2013-09-27 09:53:51"}},{"id":"1436","content_id":"3","tag_id":"143","order":"9","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"143","code":"america","name":"America","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:41:45","modified":"2013-10-25 10:41:45"}},{"id":"1437","content_id":"3","tag_id":"3","order":"10","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"3","code":"west","name":"West","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 10:26:21","modified":"2013-09-27 10:26:21"}},{"id":"1438","content_id":"3","tag_id":"147","order":"11","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"147","code":"international-relations","name":"international relations","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-11-18 11:32:59","modified":"2013-11-18 11:32:59"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"1439","content_id":"3","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"5","code":"the-thematic-areas-of-atlantic-future","user_id":"1","title":"The thematic areas of ATLANTIC FUTURE","abstract":"Four main areas have been identified as the main potential drivers for cooperation in the Atlantic. ATLANTIC FUTURE will obtain information and a mental map of the trends in these issue areas.\r\n&nbsp;","body":"<p>ATLANTIC FUTURE work focuses on four thematic areas: economy and finance, security, political, social and cultural relations, and resources and environment.<\/p>\r\n<h3 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><em>Economy and Finance<\/em><\/h3>\r\n<p>Economic links are at the forefront of the transformation of the Atlantic world. Changes in global finances are markedly reflected in the region. Global and regional economic growth is at the same time the result of and the stimulus for a large increase in trade flows and their diversification. Financial flows across the region take very different shapes: transfers resulting from trade imbalances, credit and financial investment, FDI, development aid and migrant remittances, to name only the most significant. Each of them is undergoing substantial change across the Atlantic. Tourism is also playing a growing role in linking regions together. All those flows are the background for the emergence of new routes of transportation, both over the sea and by air, and even of pan-Atlantic infrastructure, such as undersea internet cable connections.<\/p>\r\n<h3><strong><em>Security<\/em><\/strong><\/h3>\r\n<p>Compared to the Pacific or the Indian Ocean, the Atlantic does not appear as a source of global insecurities or tensions. The relations between most powers in the area are relatively cordial and where there is open antagonism, for example between Cuba and the United States, or open territorial grievances, like between Great Britain and Argentina over the Malvinas\/Falklands or between Spain and Morocco over the cities of Ceuta and Melilla, an open military conflict seems a remote possibility. However, under that quiet surface, a military build-up in Latin America serves as a reminder that not all conventional threats can be safely discarded in the Atlantic. This holds even truer for non-conventional threats. The lethal combination between fragile states, lucrative narcotics smuggling routes and vast sea and land borders that are difficult to control, links the countries on both sides of the Central Atlantic in a vicious circle of violence, poverty, instability and all forms of organised crime. As traffic grows along the Atlantic sea lanes, maritime security becomes a regional and a global concern, in particular in view of the increase in piracy activities in the Gulf of Guinea or drug trafficking across the Atlantic sores.<\/p>\r\n<h3><strong><em>People and Institutions<\/em><\/strong><\/h3>\r\n<p>Large and mid-sized players, notably emerging ones in South America and Africa, pursue a multi-vector foreign policy that result in new diplomatic and political ties. Brazil and South Africa, closely followed by other middle regional players such as Argentina, Colombia or Nigeria, feature multiple identities as developing and middle-income countries, champions of the South, protagonists of the global economy, leaders of regional cooperation and pioneers of new partnerships across the Atlantic as well as with other regions of the world. The North Atlantic actors cannot assume that predominance of democratic governance in Africa and South America will necessarily result in convergence of values and perceptions, and even less in automatic alliances on global issues. Contrasting perspectives on such crucial issues as human rights or democratisation can become significant obstacles to a wider Atlantic cooperation. The proliferation of actors and agendas challenges the traditional approach of the US and the EU towards their Southern neighbours in the Atlantic space but also bears the seeds of new opportunities for cooperation and mutual benefit. A number of variables, both internal and external to the Atlantic space, will determine whether these seeds will bear fruit.<\/p>\r\n<h3><strong><em>Resources and Environment<\/em><\/strong><\/h3>\r\n<p>Energy and climate issues, in particular, have become key Atlantic vectors, as an incipient &ldquo;Atlantic Basin energy system&rdquo; (re)emerges as an important subsystem within the global political and energy economy, alongside the Pacific and Indian Ocean Basin-systems. The energy map of the Atlantic area is one that reflects not only the very different real income and consumption levels of the Atlantic continents, but also the divergent energy economies and distinct energy policy environments and evolutions. Key global trends (including climate change, intensifying competition for resources, the imperative to eliminate poverty) are pushing in the direction of energy policy and regulatory convergence within the Atlantic Basin and toward a deepening of transatlantic energy trade and investment. The Southern Cone and Southern Africa have recently emerged as new centers of gravity within the energy landscape of the Atlantic Basin. Many new energy trends are now emerging in the Southern Atlantic, although the unconventional gas revolution in the United States is shifting energy trade patterns, and the search for renewables on each Atlantic continent also offers considerable potential for transformation. The Atlantic Basin accounts for approximately one-third of both global oil and gas production. Over 40% of world petroleum reserves and nearly 12% of global conventional gas reserves are located in the Atlantic world. These figures are also likely to increase in coming years, as more unconventional oil sources - offshore oil, Arctic oil, and shale gas - are discovered, then classified as proven reserves, and eventually brought online as new production. The Southern Atlantic alone could account for as much as 20% of global energy demand by 2035, with the entire Atlantic Basin contributing nearly half. The expected boom in Southern Atlantic energy demand lends the Atlantic Basin energy space more critical mass within the global energy system.<\/p>","views":"393","shares":"1","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2013-04-19 18:29:00","modified":"2016-02-06 09:01:53"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[],"ContentTag":[{"id":"1347","content_id":"5","tag_id":"21","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag