"ContentTag":[{"id":"6980","content_id":"1249","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"6980","content_id":"1249","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"1599","code":"atlantic-business-briefs","user_id":"1","title":"Atlantic business briefs","abstract":"<p>Business briefs&nbsp;<em>Economic and financial links in the Atlantic Space <\/em>by&nbsp;Mark Aspinwall, Centro de Investigaci&oacute;n y Docencia Econ&oacute;micas A.C. (CIDE) and<em>&nbsp;Outlook for the Fossil Fuel and Renewable Energy Industries in the Wider Atlantic Space <\/em>by&nbsp;Christoph H. Stefes and R. Andreas Kraemer Ecologic Institute Berlin<\/p>","body":"<p><em>Economic and financial links <\/em>are strong across the Atlantic space, especially the North Atlantic. While North-South and South-South links are growing, they are influenced by the presence of external factors, like China or the price of commodities. There is strong evidence of continued and lasting economic interaction among the developed Atlantic in the north, and there does appear to be some trend toward the integration of Africa and Latin America into the Atlantic (and global) trade and investment regimes, through their northern partners, partly because of the rise of emerging market economies (especially Brazil, Mexico, and South Africa) and partly because of decisions to increase South-South economic interactions.<\/p>\r\n<p><em>Fossil Fuel and Renewable Energy Industries<\/em> explains that although, the Atlantic Space holds a large share of the world&rsquo;s unexploited fossil fuel reserves, including 40% of oil reserves, 20% of natural gas reserves, and roughly 40% of coal reserves (BP 2015), the future of the industry is uncertain. Large profit margins (in the past) and continued subsides have made some of these unconventional and difficult hydrocarbon reserves easier to access via new technologies, particularly in the cases of the North Atlantic shale revolution and the Southern Atlantic &ldquo;oil ring&rdquo; ( Isbell 2014). In the North Atlantic, shale gas now accounts for more than 35% of American gas production, compared to 2% in 2000. Demand for shale oil and gas is predicted to rise from 1.96 BCM\/day to 2.69 BCM\/day by 2035 (Szalai 2013). In the Southern Atlantic oil ring, deep-water offshore oil rigs now span from Namibia and Morocco in the east to Argentina and the Gulf of Mexico (Isbell 2014), but their further expansion is in doubt given current and projected oil prices.<\/p>","views":"378","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2015-12-03 12:16:00","modified":"2016-02-08 11:52:48"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"182","content_id":"1599","type":"1","file_name":"1599-Economic and financial links in the Atlantic Space.pdf","description":"Economic and financial links in the Atlantic Space","created":"2015-12-03 12:42:22","modified":"2015-12-03 12:42:22"},{"id":"183","content_id":"1599","type":"1","file_name":"1599-Outlook for the fossil fuel and renewable energy industries in the wider Atlantic Space.pdf","description":"Outlook for the Fossil fuel and renewable energy industries in the Wider Atlantic Sapce","created":"2015-12-03 12:49:05","modified":"2015-12-03 12:49:05"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"7346","content_id":"1599","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"7338","content_id":"1599","tag_id":"20","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"20","code":"economy-and-finance","name":"Economy and finance","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"A85CA0","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-09-27 09:57:02"}},{"id":"7339","content_id":"1599","tag_id":"139","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"139","code":"asia","name":"Asia","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:25","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:25"}},{"id":"7340","content_id":"1599","tag_id":"140","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"140","code":"africa","name":"Africa","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:33","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:33"}},{"id":"7341","content_id":"1599","tag_id":"141","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"141","code":"latin-america","name":"Latin America","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:43","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:43"}},{"id":"7342","content_id":"1599","tag_id":"206","order":"5","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"206","code":"economic-integration","name":"economic integration","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7343","content_id":"1599","tag_id":"26","order":"6","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"26","code":"resources-and-environment","name":"Resources and environment","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"9AC4AB","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:08:22"}},{"id":"7344","content_id":"1599","tag_id":"108","order":"7","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"108","code":"energy","name":"Energy","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 11:04:45","modified":"2013-09-27 11:04:45"}},{"id":"7345","content_id":"1599","tag_id":"150","order":"8","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"7346","content_id":"1599","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"1532","code":"africa-and-the-eu","user_id":"1","title":"Africa and the EU","abstract":"<p>Working paper The EU and Africa:&nbsp;Regionalism and interregionalism beyond institutions, by&nbsp;Nicoletta Pirozzi,&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family: 'Open Sans', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 600; line-height: 21.92px;\">Istituto Affari Internazionali (IAI)<\/span>&nbsp;and Andr&eacute;as Gods&auml;ter,&nbsp;University of Pretoria (UP)<\/p>","body":"<p>This paper aims at mapping relevant trends of regionalism and interregionalism in and between Europe and &nbsp;Africa, by looking at the historical evolution and in light of recent developments. The analysis focuses on institutionalized regionalism and interregionalism between the European Union (EU) and the African Union (AU), as well as regional organizations in Southern, West and East Africa in the three sectors of trade; security; and environment. It also goes beyond by addressing and comparing formal and informal, state and non-state, patterns of integration at regional and transnational levels.<\/p>\r\n<p>The paper concludes that the EU and AU present many commonalties in terms of institutional architecture. Nevertheless, if we look at the reality of their achievements, it emerges that the two organizations evolved at different pace, with the AU lagging behind, also due to the fact that the integration process in the two regions is confronted with different challenges.In terms of interregional relations, it appears that the EU has heavily influenced the development of regionalism in Africa mainly through teaching and support. The relationship between the EU and African regions is fundamentally characterized by the former influencing regional policy of, and providing funds and capacity building to, the latter.<\/p>","views":"254","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2015-11-17 12:30:00","modified":"2016-02-08 14:09:42"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"178","content_id":"1532","type":"1","file_name":"1532-EU-Africa.pdf","description":"The EU and Africa: Regionalism and interregionalism beyond institutions\r\n","created":"2015-11-17 12:30:47","modified":"2015-11-17 12:30:47"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"7330","content_id":"1532","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"7324","content_id":"1532","tag_id":"287","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"287","code":"interregionalism","name":"interregionalism","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7325","content_id":"1532","tag_id":"286","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"286","code":"eu","name":"eu","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7326","content_id":"1532","tag_id":"137","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"137","code":"european-union","name":"European Union","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:16:06","modified":"2013-10-25 10:16:06"}},{"id":"7327","content_id":"1532","tag_id":"140","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"140","code":"africa","name":"Africa","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:33","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:33"}},{"id":"7328","content_id":"1532","tag_id":"178","order":"5","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"178","code":"university-of-pretoria","name":"University of Pretoria","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2014-04-24 14:52:42","modified":"2014-04-24 14:52:42"}},{"id":"7329","content_id":"1532","tag_id":"150","order":"6","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"7330","content_id":"1532","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"1530","code":"latin-america-and-the-eu","user_id":"1","title":"Latin America and the EU","abstract":"<p><strong>Working paper EU-Latin America and Caribbean Inter-regional relations: complexity and change, by&nbsp;<\/strong><strong>Gian Luca Gardini,&nbsp;<\/strong>University Erlangen-N&uuml;rnberg, and&nbsp;<strong>Anna Ayuso,&nbsp;<\/strong>CIDOB<\/p>","body":"<p>This paper analyses regionalism in Latin America and the Caribbean and interregionalism between this region and the European Union. The complexities and overlapping of Latin American regionalisms are reflected in the several interregional mechanisms that the European Union has with Latin American and Caribbean countries and regional organisations. The paper argues that different political and economic interests in Latin America and the Caribbean have given rise to overlapping regionalist projects, where the overlapping of competences is more problematic than that of membership. Also, Latin American and Caribbean regionalisms have constantly evolved in terms of strategies and organisations. This has generated a number of interregional institutionalized mechanisms between the EU and Latin America and the Caribbean, but the current structure seems in need for reform.<\/p>","views":"195","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2015-11-17 12:25:00","modified":"2016-02-08 04:57:40"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"