FFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"7315","content_id":"1530","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"1518","code":"brussels-a-transformed-atlantic-space","user_id":"1","title":"Brussels: A transformed Atlantic Space","abstract":"<p>Final dissemination event in Brussels:&nbsp;<strong>A transformed Atlantic Space: Emerging trends and future scenarios for Europe<\/strong><\/p>","body":"<p><strong>A transformed Atlantic Space: Emerging trends and future scenarios for Europe<\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p>Join us in the final dissemination event of the Atlantic Future project in Brussels.&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p>We are pleased to invite you to the event &ldquo;A transformed Atlantic Space: Emerging trends and future scenarios for Europe&rdquo; on 10 December in Brussels.<\/p>\r\n<p>The event will mark the end of the research project <a href=\"..\/..\/..\/..\/\">Atlantic Future<\/a>. Our experts will provide new perspectives on the Atlantic space and on the policy approaches to this region, and will present the new web-based &ldquo;Atlas of the Atlantic&rdquo;.<\/p>\r\n<p>The Atlantic can be considered the cradle of modern globalisation, a space where links between peoples, nations and economies started first to transcend their regional contexts on a large scale. As globalisation enters a new phase and as global challenges such as the economic crises, food security, terrorism, climate change or energy scarcity become more urgent, the states and regions around the Atlantic look at their counterparts across the ocean with renewed interest.<\/p>\r\n<p>Join us in what promises to be an engaging discussion.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Date<\/strong>: 10 December 2015<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Time<\/strong>: 9.15-14.15<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Venue<\/strong>: Center for European Policy Studies (CEPS), Working Party Room - 3rd floor, Place du Congr&egrave;s, 1 -1000 Brussels<\/p>\r\n<p>To confirm your attendance, please confirm at <a href=\"mailto:activitats@cidob.org\">activitats@cidob.org<\/a><\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Agenda attached<\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"707","shares":"1","tweets":"4","mails":"1","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"1","created":"2015-11-17 12:07:00","modified":"2016-02-08 14:09:30"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":"1518","datetime":"2015-12-10 09:00:00","country":"Belgium","city":"Brussels","address":"Congresplaats 1, Brussels (CEPS)","map":""},"Resource":[{"id":"181","content_id":"1518","type":"1","file_name":"1518-ATLANTIC FUTURE_A transformed Atlantic Space_Brussels.pdf","description":"Brussels agenda","created":"2015-12-02 19:52:47","modified":"2015-12-02 19:52:47"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"7165","content_id":"1518","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"7162","content_id":"1518","tag_id":"137","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"137","code":"european-union","name":"European Union","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:16:06","modified":"2013-10-25 10:16:06"}},{"id":"7163","content_id":"1518","tag_id":"283","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"283","code":"brussels","name":"brussels","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7164","content_id":"1518","tag_id":"43","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"43","code":"policy","name":"Policy","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 10:04:43","modified":"2013-09-27 10:04:43"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"7165","content_id":"1518","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"1131","code":"atlantic-voices-with-r-andreas-kraemer","user_id":"1","title":"Atlantic Voices with R. Andreas Kraemer","abstract":"<p>Discover the insights of the Atlantic energy system. An interview with R. Andreas Kraemer,&nbsp;Founder &amp; Director Emeritus of <a href=\"http:\/\/www.ecologic.eu\/\">Ecologic Institute<\/a> in Berlin.<\/p>","body":"<p><em>R. Andreas Kraemer is Founder &amp; Director Emeritus of&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/www.ecologic.eu\/\">Ecologic Institute<\/a> in Berlin, Germany, and Founding Chairman (pro bono) of <a href=\"http:\/\/www.eius.org\">Ecologic Institute US<\/a> in Washington DC. He is currently Senior Fellow at the <a href=\"http:\/\/www.iass-potsdam.de\/en\/\">Institute for Advanced Sustainability Studies<\/a> (IASS) in Potsdam, Germany, and Visiting Assistant Professor of Political Science &amp; Adjunct Professor of German Studies at <a href=\"http:\/\/www.duke.edu\">Duke University<\/a>, where he teaches on evolution environmental policy&nbsp; in the context of European integration. From April to June 2015, he was Visiting Scholar at the <a href=\"http:\/\/web.mit.edu\/\">Massachusetts Institute of Technology<\/a> (MIT), Center for Energy and Environmental Policy Research (<a href=\"http:\/\/ceepr.mit.edu\/\">CEEPR<\/a>). His current research focuses on the role and functions of science-based policy institutes or \"think tanks\" in theory and practice, the interactions among policy domains and international relations, and global governance on environment, resources, climate and energy<\/em>.&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Q: <\/strong><strong>What do you see when you look at the energy sector through an Atlantic lens?<\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p>A: The world&rsquo;s energy systems are Atlantic. This is true for coal, the fuel that started the industrial revolution and powered industry and especially mining. It is also true for other fossil energy carriers: oil including shale oil and tar sands and methane. The nuclear industry started in the WWII era in the North Atlantic and financially sustained by Atlantic government subsidies before going global.&nbsp; The recent onset of fracking is an essentially North American phenomenon.<\/p>\r\n<p>Early development of renewable energy technologies including solar energy and wind turbines started in the US before globalizing. Bio-energy at industrial scale is also of Atlantic provenance, from sugar cane to alcohol as transport fuel in Brazil, corn-to-ethanol for fuel blending in the US, to canola (rape seed) to bio-diesel or general agricultural waste to biogas to bio-genic electricity in the EU.&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Q: <\/strong><strong>What are the trends and dynamics of energy in the Atlantic space?&nbsp; <\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p>A: Nuclear power and fossil energies are declining due to generally rising long-term costs. Many companies are heading for write-downs, economic abandonment or insolvency and possible government bail-outs. The Atlantic nations have overdeveloped both fossil and nuclear energy, incurring enormous political and security costs, e.g. climate change.<\/p>\r\n<p>Renewable energy development and use is increasing, but at different rates and sometimes from a low starting basis. Cost improvements result from new inventions, material discoveries as well as technological, business, and policy learning curves, particularly for solar energy and storage. The roll-out of IT-based technology is accelerating both in relation to existing technologies and the investment and development of new energy systems. This transformation is proving disruptive to the old, dirty and dangerous fossil and nuclear energy industries. The Age of Energy Transformation away from fossil and nuclear towards renewable energy supply with storage in a smart grid is originally an Atlantic phenomenon, conceived as an idea by Amory Lovins of the Rocky Mountain Institute in the US, and now epitomised by the German \"Energiewende\" entering practically all Atlantic languages.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Q: What does the Atlantic future energy system look like?<\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p>A: While the true costs of fossil and nuclear systems are becoming ever more obvious, pressure mounts for public budgets to phase-out the perverse subsidies that favour them. Energy efficiency, renewable and storage technologies are becoming ever cheaper. As a consequence, energy-related trade and investment patterns will change. Instead of energy carriers such as coal and gas being traded, it will be equipment for renewable power generation and storage for various kinds. The total cost of energy supply will decline, and asset values of energy infrastructure will fall. More energy will be consumed close to the point of production.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Q:&nbsp;What are the trigger points of potential cooperation in the Atlantic space?<\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p>A: Atlantic nations should cooperate to accelerate the energy transformation. A key measure is reforming energy-related taxation, including scrapping perverse subsidies and privileges for fossil and nuclear energy. Governments should agree to facilitate the trade in goods and services relating to energy efficiency, renewable energies, storage and smart grids. Tariffs still imposed should be removed, perhaps by \"coordinated unilateralism\".&nbsp; Local, regional or national content obligations in government procurement rules should be scrapped. In order to facilitate the trade in biogenic energy, stringent sustainability criteria should be agreed for the production and processing of biomass. The Atlantic nations might follow the \"top-runner\" approach so that the best practice concerning energy efficiency or energy conversion in any one country or company becomes the norm after 3 or 5 years. That would speed invention, innovation and dissemination of desirable technologies throughout the Atlantic space.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Download the Atlantic Voices here:<\/strong><\/p>","views":"952","shares":"0","tweets":"2","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2015-10-08 17:13:00","modified":"2016-02-08 04:00:01"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"171","content_id":"1131","type":"1","file_name":"1131-ATLANTIC VOICES_02_R.A. Kraemer.pdf","description":"Atlantic Voices #2 with R. Andreas Kraemer","created":"2015-10-08 09:42:43","modified":"2015-10-08 09:42:43"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"6792","content_id":"1131","tag_id":"26","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"26","code":"resources-and-environment","name":"Resources and environment","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"9AC4AB","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:08:22"}},{"id":"6786","content_id":"1131","tag_id":"108","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"108","code":"energy","name":"Energy","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 11:04:45","modified":"2013-09-27 11:04:45"}},{"id":"6787","content_id":"1131","tag_id":"237","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"237","code":"fossil-fuels","name":"fossil fuels","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"6788","content_id":"1131","tag_id":"190","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"190","code":"r-andreas-kraemer","name":"r. andreas kraemer","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"6789","content_id":"1131","tag_id":"174","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"174","code":"ecologic-institute","name":"ecologic institute","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"6790","content_id":"1131","tag_id":"279","order":"5","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"279","code":"renewables","name":"renewables","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"6791","content_id":"1131","tag_id":"280","order":"6","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"280","code":"nuclear","name":"nuclear","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"6792","content_id":"1131","tag_id":"26","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"26","code":"resources-and-environment","name":"Resources and environment","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"9AC4AB","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:08:22"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"1108","code":"views-from-international-organizations","user_id":"1","title":"Views from international organizations","abstract":"<p><strong>Two papers present perspectives and perceptions on the Atlantic space from international organizations. The papers expose the results of interviews carried out in Geneva, New York and Washington DC.<\/strong><\/p>","body":"<p><strong>Perspectives from International Organizations in Geneva <\/strong>(by Paula de Castro,CIDOB)<\/p>\r\n<p>The purpose of this paper was to take the pulse of what international organisation representatives in Geneva perceived about the Atlantic, while providing evidence to answer the Atlantic Future project research question on whether a new pan-Atlantic system of relations is emerging in the Atlantic beyond the traditional North Atlantic alliance and the North-South dependency. With this objective in mind regional trends and dynamics have been presented and analysed in this paper. However, interviewees not only had particular difficulty thinking about the Atlantic in terms of a unified geopolitical space but also agreed that, for the time being at least, we could not speak of the emergence of this geopolitical space. Because, despite the common ground that exists among the regions of the Atlantic, the context of international reconfiguration being experienced today, and the prevalence of national and regional dynamics still have direct impact on the social and political mindset of the Atlantic sub-regions. For the interviewees, the notion of the Atlantic space is simply not in the quintessence&nbsp;of the region and lacks the political leadership that is needed for this.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Perspectives from International Organizations in New York and Washington, D.C.<\/strong>(by Elizabeth Tedsen,Ecologic Institute)<\/p>\r\n<p>The conventional dynamics of pan-Atlantic relations and North-South dichotomy have changed dramatically over the past ten to twenty years, with Southern countries rising to greater economic and political prominence. Fundamental changes are taking place within and between Atlantic countries, yet many of these are eclipsed by, or ultimately part of, growing globalization and multipolarity. These may be accompanied by the relative decline of the European Union as it turns inward to meet internal challenges and as political and economic gravities shift. Historical and cultural ties provide a deep foundation for interregional cooperation between Atlantic countries on issues such as trade, drug trafficking, and governance of shared commons.&nbsp; Yet whether these ties can form the basis for a new &ldquo;Atlantic Rim,&rdquo; or whether instead the dynamics and trends within the Atlantic herald an increasingly interconnected and globalized world whereby the relevance of these linkages weakens, remains to be seen.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Download the two papers here:<\/strong>&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"162","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2015-10-07 10:17:00","modified":"2016-02-03 05:20:35"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"145","content_id":"1108","type":"1","file_name":"1108-ATLANTIC FUTURE_Perspectives from IO in Geneva.pdf","description":"Perspectives from International Organizations in Geneva (by Paula de Castro, CIDOB)","created":"2015-09-08 10:18:02","modified":"2015-09-08 10:18:02"},{"id":"146","content_id":"1108","type":"1","file_name":"1108-ATLANTIC FUTURE_ Perspectives from New York and Washington.pdf","description":"Perspectives from International Organizations in New York and Washington, D.C. (by Elizabeth Tedsen, Ecologic Institute)","created":"2015-09-08 10:18:23","modified":"2015-09-08 10:18:23"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"7445","content_id":"1108","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"7433","content_id":"1108","tag_id":"54","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"54","code":"perspectives","name":"Perspectives","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 10:43:59","modified":"2013-09-27 10:43:59"}},{"id":"7434","content_id":"1108","tag_id":"254","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"254","code":"perceptions","name":"perceptions","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7435","content_id":"1108","tag_id":"5","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"5","code":"atlantic-space","name":"Atlantic space","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 09:55:08","modified":"2013-09-27 09:55:08"}},{"id":"7436","content_id":"1108","tag_id":"137","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"137","code":"european-union","name":"European Union","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:16:06","modified":"2013-10-25 10:16:06"}},{"id":"7437","content_id":"1108","tag_id":"255","order":"5","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"255","code":"eu-role","name":"eu role","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7438","content_id":"1108","tag_id":"256","order":"6","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"256","code":"values","name":"values","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7439","content_id":"1108","tag_id":"139","order":"7","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"139","code":"asia","name":"Asia","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:25","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:25"}},{"id":"7440","content_id":"1108","tag_id":"186","order":"8","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"186","code":"ttip","name":"ttip","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7441","content_id":"1108","tag_id":"140","order":"9","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"140","code":"africa","name":"Africa","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:33","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:33"}},{"id":"7442","content_id":"1108","tag_id":"41","order":"10","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"41","code":"actors","name":"Actors","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 09:53:51","modified":"2013-09-27 09:53:51"}},{"id":"7443","content_id":"1108","tag_id":"257","order":"11","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"257","code":"interests","name":"interests","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7444","content_id":"1108","tag_id":"150","order":"12","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"7445","content_id":"1108","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"1111","code":"perspectives-from-europe","user_id":"1","title":"Perspectives from Europe","abstract":"<p><strong>Nine papers present perspectives and perceptions on the Atlantic space across the European Union. The papers expose the results of interviews carried out in Brussels, France, Portugal, Spain, Germany, Italy, Poland, United Kingdom and the Netherlands. &nbsp;<\/strong><\/p>","body":"<p><strong>Perspectives from Brussels <\/strong>(by Elisa Lled&oacute;, FRIDE, and Danielle Piatkiewicz, GMF)<\/p>\r\n<p>Is a new pan-Atlantic system of relations emerging in the Atlantic space beyond the traditional North Atlantic alliance and the North-South dependency? Although there was no unanimous opinion, many interviewees from various sectors in Brussels appeared to be sceptical about this potential scenario (there was a strong EU-US transatlantic space but weak relations with the South), while others claimed that the Atlantic Basin could be more interconnected, mainly in economic terms. GMF and FRIDE, with their respective offices used their networks to interview the relevant actors based on their professional and academic expertise. The main concerns regarding the current state and future of the Atlantic region included, amongst others: the future of the TTIP trade negotiation between the US and the EU, the lack of a cohesive &ldquo;Atlantic&rdquo; security approach, the struggle for a united and common energy and climate and environmental policy within the Atlantic space.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;<\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Perspectives from France <\/strong>(by Danielle Piatkiewicz and Bruno Medroa, GMF)<\/p>\r\n<p>The Atlantic Future project explores the concept that new relations are emerging in the Atlantic space beyond the traditional North Atlantic alliance and the North-South dependency. GMF, with their respective office in Paris, France, used their networks to interview the relevant actors based on their professional and academic expertise. The main consensus on the emergence of a pan- Atlantic space was mixed. The main concerns on the current and future state of the Atlantic region from the Paris perspective touched on the following;&nbsp; future of the trade and investment, along with the negotiation of free trade agreements such as the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) between the U.S. and the EU. The respondents identified the need for different priorities between North and South Atlantic. It was strongly expressed that Europe and the U.S. remain the most important actors for the global economy, along with China and India. However, countries like Brazil or South Africa have been rising as economic models rather than as economic powers, and show an increased influence from the Southern Atlantic countries.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Perspectives from Portugal <\/strong>(by Daniel Marcos,IPRI-NOVA University)<\/p>\r\n<p>The creation of a pan-Atlantic space, based on cooperation between the different regions of the Atlantic is fundamental for the future of the Atlantic basin, capable to deal with the emergence of new powers in the Asia-Pacific Rim and the threats that emerged with the end of the Cold War: terrorism, migration trends, illicit trafficking, fragile states, etc. The analysis of four specific areas &ndash; economy and finances, security, people and institutions, resources and environment &ndash; has shown the existence of different stages of development of the Atlantic basin countries, mainly between the North and the South, which must be overcome by cooperation in these same areas. For Portuguese stakeholders, the European Union, African Union and NATO have a fundamental role to play, but EU is mostly seen as a role model to be followed for the development of regional and interregional cooperation. The challenge is to overcome the lack of leadership of EU in the last 5 years and the traditional suspicion of the South Atlantic regarding to the North in order to deepen the relations between the shores of the Atlantic.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Perspectives from Spain <\/strong>(by Susanne Gratius, FRIDE)<\/p>\r\n<p>The perceptions and opinions of Spanish stakeholders on the Atlantic are highly diverse but coincide in the need to include Latin America in Transatlantic relations. Most interviewees in Spain focused on economic aspects and security interests in the Atlantic, while people and institutions, resources and environment ranked second. The overwhelming majority of interviewees shared a rather sceptical view on the future of the Atlantic as an articulated and institutionalized space or a community of values. There was also a consensus on the view that Latin America is part of the Atlantic identity, while Africa is more distant in terms of values and norms, development and common interest. The North-South divide is still present, but most interviewees agreed on the need for a more balanced and horizontal relationship taking into account the power shifts towards regional leaders like Brazil, Mexico or South Africa, on the one hand, and multinational companies and &ldquo;global civil society networks, on the other.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Perspectives from Germany&nbsp;<\/strong>(by Christoph H. Stefes,Ecologic Institute Berlin)<\/p>\r\n<p>The twenty individuals from Germany interviewed for this project emphasized the critical importance of transatlantic relations for Europe. Despite its relative decline in power, the United States is still considered Europe&rsquo;s most important security and economic partner. The interviewees accordingly emphasized the need to conclude the current TTIP negotiations successfully. The emergence of a pan-Atlantic community on the other hand met more scepticism, as interviewees pointed towards the still existing lack of consolidated liberal democracies and resilient markets in Latin America and even more so in Africa. Moreover, they perceived a lack of common values and shared interests across the regions of the South Atlantic and the regions of the North Atlantic.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Perspectives from Italy&nbsp;<\/strong>(by Andrea Dess&igrave; and Chiara Rosselli,Istituto Affari Internazionali)<\/p>\r\n<p>On the whole sceptical about the notion of an emerging pan-Atlantic space, Italian stakeholders converged around the necessity of strengthening the transatlantic relationship as the primary means to ensure a continued relevance on the world stage and greater conformity to EU-US norms and standards among Atlantic countries. While impossible to ignore the rising influence of Asia and China in the Atlantic, Europe and the US maintain certain margins of influence and leverage within this space. Supportive of the TTIP, stakeholders emphasised Europe&rsquo;s internal divisions, a lack of trust and the persistence of paternalism in North-South relations as the primary obstacles for the emergence of closer cooperation among Atlantic countries.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Perspectives from Poland <\/strong>(by Corinna H\u04e7rst and Danielle Piatkiewicz,GMF)<\/p>\r\n<p>The concept of a new pan-Atlantic system of relations emerging in the Atlantic space beyond the traditional North Atlantic alliance and the North-South dependency has captured the Atlantic space. Polish interviewees from Warsaw viewed the idea with a measure of scepticism. Although there was no unanimous opinion, many interviewees from various sectors in Warsaw appeared to be sceptical about this potential scenario stating that the lack of a unified EU and Europe could prevent this idea from forming. The German Marshall Fund of the United States (GMF) and their Warsaw based office used their networks to interview the relevant actors based on their professional and academic expertise. The overall main concerns regarding the current state and future of the Atlantic region included, amongst others: the current and future state of transatlantic relations, the future of the TTIP trade negotiation between the US and the EU, the lack of a cohesive &ldquo;Atlantic&rdquo; security approach, the U.S.&rsquo;s shift towards other regions, and the lack of a cohesive energy and climate and environmental policy both within the EU and the Atlantic space.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Perspectives from the UK <\/strong>(by Sangeeta Khorana and Christina Stolte)<\/p>\r\n<p>Interviews in London informed us about the stakeholders&rsquo; perceptions in four thematic areas of the Atlantic Future project, which include: economy and finance, security, people and institutions, resources and environment. Main themes of focus were: changes over the past 20 years; drivers for change or continuity; prospective view of the changes and continuities in the region; actors and regional leaders (state or non-state level); relevance of the EU; perceptions on the evolution of the EU&rsquo;s role in the region over the past 20 years; and finally the convergence or divergence of norms within the Atlantic space. Based on the interview results in the UK, the paper reports that developments in the Atlantic have led to a proliferation of economic and non-economic initiatives amongst various Atlantic actors, both in the North and South. In the North, the North Atlantic community and the USA and EU is undergoing major changes in economic, security and political terms. Following the spectacular rise of Brazil and Africa, the focus has been gradually shifting from the EU and USA and new dynamics is evolving in the Atlantic space. However, a Pan Atlantic space is not really emerging but if the ongoing Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) between the EU and USA were successful this could herald the beginning of a new Atlantic space. The EU is and continues to be an important player in the Atlantic, and is likely to play an influential role in the reconfiguration of the Atlantic space.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Perspectives from the Netherlands <\/strong>(by Lucy Olivia Smith,Ecologic Institute Berlin)<\/p>\r\n<p>Twenty individuals from the Netherlands were interviewed for this report on transatlantic geopolitics. While the North-Atlantic relationships between Europe and the US remains strong and established in issues related to security and economy, the project sought to gauge whether there was a budding pan-Atlantic community. Rather than confirm this idea, the interviewees highlighted the emergence of substantial emerging economies in Latin America and Africa and through this observation, emphasized the increasing polarity of the international community that is increasingly defined by diverse axis of power and significance and less so by traditional power blocs. While some specific topics had a distinctly Atlantic dimension, such as the issue of immigration and drug trafficking, most matters related to economy and security were firmly entrenched in the reality of a truly globalised world. When forming ideas of how Europe could maintain relevance, several interviewees saw the EU as a model for supra-national governance structures and demilitarisation and as defining itself in a soft power role.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Download the nine papers here:<\/strong>&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"166","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2015-10-07 07:55:00","modified":"2016-02-06 21:57:23"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"149","content_id":"1111","type":"1","file_name":"1111-AF_WP7_ Deliverable 7.2.pdf","description":"Introduction","created":"2015-09-08 10:57:01","modified":"2015-09-08 10:57:01"},{"id":"150","content_id":"1111","type":"1","file_name":"1111-ATLANTIC FUTURE_ Perspectives from Belgium_Brussels.pdf","description":"Perspectives from Brussels (by Elisa Lled\u00f3, FRIDE, and Danielle Piatkiewicz, GMF)","created":"2015-09-08 10:57:36","modified":"2015-09-08 10:57:36"},{"id":"151","content_id":"1111","type":"1","file_name":"1111-ATLANTIC FUTURE_ Perspecties from France_ Paris.pdf","description":"Perspectives from France (by Danielle Piatkiewicz and Bruno Medroa, GMF)","created":"2015-09-08 10:58:00","modified":"2015-09-08 10:58:00"},{"id":"152","content_id":"1111","type":"1","file_name":"1111-ATLANTIC FUTURE_ Perspectives from Portugal.pdf","description":"Perspectives from Portugal (by Daniel Marcos, IPRI-NOVA University)","created":"2015-09-08 10:58:22","modified":"2015-09-08 10:58:22"},{"id":"153","content_id":"1111","type":"1","file_name":"1111-ATLANTIC FUTURE_ Perspectives from Spain_ Madrid.pdf","description":"Perspectives from Spain (by Susanne Gratius, FRIDE)","created":"2015-09-08 10:59:03","modified":"2015-09-08 10:59:03"},{"id":"154","content_id":"1111","type":"1","file_name":"1111-ATLANTIC FUTURE_ Perspectives from Germany.pdf","description":"Perspectives from Germany (by Christoph H. Stefes, Ecologic Institute Berlin)","created":"2015-09-08 10:59:21","modified":"2015-09-08 10:59:21"},{"id":"155","content_id":"1111","type":"1","file_name":"1111-ATLANTIC FUTURE_ Perspectives from Italy.pdf","description":"Perspectives from Italy (by Andrea Dess\u00ec and Chiara Rosselli, Istituto Affari Internazionali)","created":"2015-09-08 11:00:01","modified":"2015-09-08 11:00:01"},{"id":"156","content_id":"1111","type":"1","file_name":"1111-ATLANTIC FUTURE_ Perspectives from Poland_Warsaw.pdf","description":"Perspectives from Poland (