olor":"EBC635","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:04:26"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"329","code":"development-in-the-atlantic","user_id":"1","title":"Development in the Atlantic","abstract":"<p><strong>ATLANTIC FUTURE scientific paper no. 11 is out: \"Development in the Atlantic: Between cooperation and competition\", by <\/strong><strong>Madeleine Goerg<\/strong><strong> at&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/www.gmfus.org\/\">The German Marshall Fund of the United States<\/a><\/strong><\/p>","body":"<p>This paper offers an analysis of the changing nature of development cooperation and its potential for innovation in the Atlantic sphere, particularly under the consideration of a stronger and more assertive role of southern actors. Development cooperation is indicative of broader shifts in political, economic, and cultural clout and key elements of the global aid architecture are adapting a new reality. In light of South-South Cooperation&rsquo;s emergence as an alternative to traditional aid, the analysis of cooperation in the Atlantic Basin points to an increasingly diverse global South. The diversity, in turn could position the Atlantic as a laboratory for innovative approaches to development cooperation. In the foreseeable future, interaction among Atlantic development partners, whether through cooperation, coordination, or competition, is unlikely to be crystalized into a new institutional set-up but will rather become the sum of dynamic and flexible arrangements reflecting the diversity of actors, interests, and strategies.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Download the paper here:<\/strong>&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"454","shares":"0","tweets":"1","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2014-09-29 13:56:00","modified":"2016-02-08 14:09:44"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"71","content_id":"329","type":"1","file_name":"329-ATLANTIC FUTURE_11_Development in the Atlantic.pdf","description":"Scientific paper no. 11: \u201cDevelopment in the Atlantic: Between cooperation and competition\u201d","created":"2014-09-29 13:57:14","modified":"2014-09-29 13:57:14"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"4138","content_id":"329","tag_id":"25","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"25","code":"people-and-institutions","name":"People and institutions","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"EBC635","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:04:26"}},{"id":"4134","content_id":"329","tag_id":"126","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"126","code":"cooperation","name":"Cooperation","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-30 10:21:56","modified":"2013-09-30 10:21:56"}},{"id":"4135","content_id":"329","tag_id":"15","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"15","code":"south-atlantic","name":"South Atlantic","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 11:29:49","modified":"2013-09-27 11:29:49"}},{"id":"4136","content_id":"329","tag_id":"157","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"157","code":"german-marshall-fund","name":"german marshall fund","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"4137","content_id":"329","tag_id":"150","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"4138","content_id":"329","tag_id":"25","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"25","code":"people-and-institutions","name":"People and institutions","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"EBC635","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:04:26"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"328","code":"ideas--norms-and-principles-","user_id":"1","title":"Ideas, Norms and Principles ","abstract":"<p><strong>ATLANTIC FUTURE scientific paper no. 10 is out: \"Convergence or Divergence of Ideas, Norms, and Principles in the Atlantic? The Case of Transnational Environmental Networks\", by Camilla Adelle, Lorenzo Fioramonti and Jacob Mati,&nbsp;<\/strong><strong><a href=\"http:\/\/governanceinnovation.org\/wordpress\/\">GovInn<\/a> at <a href=\"http:\/\/web.up.ac.za\/\">University of Pretoria<\/a>.<\/strong><\/p>","body":"<p>This paper is part of a wider investigation into the emergence (or not) of an Atlantic &lsquo;space&rsquo;. In other words whether the idea of a &lsquo;pan-Atlantic area&rsquo; is a viable political, social, and cultural concept. More specifically, it explores whether or not the Atlantic space can be characterized as an area of normative convergence. To do so the paper employs insights from the literatures on policy convergence and policy transfer and in particular the &lsquo;soft&rsquo; transfer of policy inputs through transnational networks. Rather than attempt to map the intangible transfer of ideas, norms, and principles across the Atlantic space, the approach taken here is to map the structures through which soft transfer can potentially take place. An analysis of online survey&nbsp;data from 150 environmental NGOs based in Europe, Africa and the Americas reveals a concentration of transnational networks within the Atlantic space, which could potentially contribute to the convergence of ideas, norms, and principles in the area. In this way, the paper argues that the pattern of transnational networks observed provides some supporting evidence of the emergence of an Atlantic space.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Download the paper here:<\/strong>&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"201","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2014-09-29 13:54:00","modified":"2016-01-31 12:55:00"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"70","content_id":"328","type":"1","file_name":"328-ATLANTIC FUTURE_10_Convergence or Divergence of Ideas Norms and Principles.pdf","description":"Scientific paper no. 10: \"Convergence or Divergence of Ideas, Norms, and Principles in the Atlantic? The Case of Transnational Environmental Networks\"","created":"2014-09-29 13:55:14","modified":"2014-09-29 13:55:14"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"4210","content_id":"328","tag_id":"25","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"25","code":"people-and-institutions","name":"People and institutions","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"EBC635","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:04:26"}},{"id":"4205","content_id":"328","tag_id":"222","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"222","code":"norms","name":"norms","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"4206","content_id":"328","tag_id":"223","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"223","code":"ideas","name":"ideas","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"4207","content_id":"328","tag_id":"224","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"224","code":"principles","name":"principles","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"4208","content_id":"328","tag_id":"178","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"178","code":"university-of-pretoria","name":"University of Pretoria","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2014-04-24 14:52:42","modified":"2014-04-24 14:52:42"}},{"id":"4209","content_id":"328","tag_id":"150","order":"5","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"4210","content_id":"328","tag_id":"25","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"25","code":"people-and-institutions","name":"People and institutions","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"EBC635","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:04:26"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"327","code":"fragile-states-in-the-atlantic","user_id":"1","title":"Fragile states in the Atlantic","abstract":"<p><strong>ATLANTIC FUTURE scientific paper no. 9 is out: \"Fragile States: Challenges and Opportunities for Atlantic Relations\", by Fernanda Faria at<\/strong>&nbsp;<strong><a href=\"http:\/\/www.gmfus.org\/\">The German Marshall Fund of the United States<\/a><\/strong><\/p>","body":"<p>Concerns over the impact of fragile states in human security, stability and development at national as well as regional and international levels are generally shared by actors across the Atlantic regions, but differences in the understanding of fragility and in approaches to fragile states are affecting dialogue and wider cooperation across the Atlantic. The changing&nbsp;geopolitical context in the Atlantic basin and globally is redefining power relations and questioning dominant policy approaches. This is creating new political space and opportunities for Southern Atlantic actors to develop their own institutional frameworks for South-South dialogue and cooperation, distinct from Northern dominated political, economic and security structures, and allow them to develop autonomous options to address common fragility trends, &lsquo;among equals&rsquo;. The geopolitical reality of the Atlantic basin is however far more complex. It extends beyond the Atlantic regions and develops in parallel tracks of competition and cooperation along North-South and South-South asymmetries and convergence. Shared interest and concerns over the impact of fragility and in specific fragile contexts provide an opportunity to test whether and how Atlantic diversity can generate new momentum and more effective approaches to address fragility in the Atlantic space.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Download the paper here:<\/strong>&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"342","shares":"0","tweets":"1","mails":"1","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2014-09-29 12:47:00","modified":"2016-02-06 20:02:55"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"92","content_id":"327","type":"1","file_name":"327-ATLANTIC FUTURE_09_Fragiles states.compressed.pdf","description":"Scientific paper no. 9: \"Fragile States: Challenges and Opportunities for Atlantic Relations\"","created":"2014-10-09 10:17:26","modified":"2014-10-09 10:17:26"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"4216","content_id":"327","tag_id":"21","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"21","code":"security","name":"Security","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"C31F4A","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:08:37"}},{"id":"4211","content_id":"327","tag_id":"130","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"130","code":"human-security","name":"Human security","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-10 11:59:29","modified":"2013-10-10 11:59:29"}},{"id":"4212","content_id":"327","tag_id":"15","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"15","code":"south-atlantic","name":"South Atlantic","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 11:29:49","modified":"2013-09-27 11:29:49"}},{"id":"4213","content_id":"327","tag_id":"140","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"140","code":"africa","name":"Africa","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:33","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:33"}},{"id":"4214","content_id":"327","tag_id":"157","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"157","code":"german-marshall-fund","name":"german marshall fund","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"4215","content_id":"327","tag_id":"150","order":"5","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"4216","content_id":"327","tag_id":"21","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"21","code":"security","name":"Security","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"C31F4A","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:08:37"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"326","code":"transnational-threats-in-the-atlantic","user_id":"1","title":"Transnational threats in the Atlantic","abstract":"<p><strong>ATLANTIC FUTURE scientific paper no. 8 is out: \"Significant Trends in Illicit Trafficking: A Macro View of the Problem and Potential Means to Address It\", by Dr. Mark R. Jacobson and Max Daurora at<\/strong>&nbsp;<strong><a href=\"http:\/\/www.gmfus.org\/\">The German Marshall Fund of the United States<\/a><\/strong><\/p>","body":"<p>The following paper provides an evaluation of recent trends relating to weapons, drug, human, and animal trafficking. The resulting conclusions will be scrutinized in order to determine the extent to which these threats impact the broader security environment within the Atlantic space. While trends pertaining to weapons, drug, human, and wildlife trafficking vary in terms of growth, a growing convergence of trafficking, organized crime, and terrorism has emerged. By examining general trends in these illicit industries, in addition to several country-specific and regional cases, a framework for an overall counter trafficking strategy can be developed. This strategy should be a holistic approach aimed at collectively addressing the various zones of criminal activity as well as integrating synchronized national efforts to curb the threat posed by these trades.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Download the paper here:<\/strong>&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"310","shares":"0","tweets":"1","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2014-09-29 12:45:00","modified":"2016-02-07 20:26:34"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"addre