0","Tag":{"id":"218","code":"terrorism","name":"terrorism","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"4156","content_id":"326","tag_id":"150","order":"6","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"4157","content_id":"326","tag_id":"21","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"21","code":"security","name":"Security","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"C31F4A","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:08:37"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"325","code":"maritime-security-in-the-atlantic","user_id":"1","title":"Maritime Security in the Atlantic","abstract":"<p><strong>ATLANTIC FUTURE scientific paper no. 7 is out: \"Maritime Territorial Delimitation and Maritime Security in the Atlantic\", by In&ecirc;s Sousa,&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/portal.fgv.br\/\">Funda&ccedil;&atilde;o Getulio Vargas<\/a>.<\/strong><\/p>","body":"<p>The present paper aims to assess how a redefined Atlantic space, based on common opportunities and challenges, could reinforce the maritime security status of the region. Far from being homogeneous, the Atlantic Basin combines different historical and cultural backgrounds, diverse natural features, and distinct levels of development. While these favour numerous&nbsp;economic and political opportunities, they may represent an obstacle in tackling maritime security issues. Through the present study, maritime border disputes are identified and mapped, and a further analysis about its impacts on interstate relations is developed. We conclude that, although there are obstacles fostering cooperation on maritime security, such cooperation is becoming increasingly relevant to the North and South Atlantic in terms of management of territorial disputes, impacts of climate change, resource protection, regulation of the maritime system and prevention of international crime.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Download the paper here:<\/strong>&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"258","shares":"0","tweets":"0","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2014-09-29 12:42:00","modified":"2016-02-01 16:23:29"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"67","content_id":"325","type":"1","file_name":"325-ATLANTIC FUTURE_07_Maritime Security in the Atlantic.pdf","description":"Scientific paper no. 7: \"Maritime Territorial Delimitation and Maritime Security in the Atlantic\"","created":"2014-09-29 12:43:46","modified":"2014-09-29 12:43:46"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"4167","content_id":"325","tag_id":"21","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"21","code":"security","name":"Security","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"C31F4A","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:08:37"}},{"id":"4163","content_id":"325","tag_id":"167","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"167","code":"fundacao-getulio-vargas-fgv-rio-de-janeiro","name":"funda\u00e7ao get\u00falio vargas (fgv) rio de janeiro","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"4164","content_id":"325","tag_id":"168","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"168","code":"-brazil","name":" brazil","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"4165","content_id":"325","tag_id":"208","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"208","code":"maritime-security","name":"maritime security","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"4166","content_id":"325","tag_id":"150","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"4167","content_id":"325","tag_id":"21","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"21","code":"security","name":"Security","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"C31F4A","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:08:37"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"324","code":"the-atlantic-as-a-new-security-area","user_id":"1","title":"The Atlantic as a new security area?","abstract":"<p><strong>ATLANTIC FUTURE scientific paper no. 6 is out: \"The Atlantic as a new security area? Current engagements and prospects for security cooperation between Africa and its Atlantic counterparts\", by John Kotsopoulos,<\/strong>&nbsp;<strong><a href=\"http:\/\/governanceinnovation.org\/wordpress\/\">GovInn<\/a> at <a href=\"http:\/\/web.up.ac.za\/\">University of Pretoria<\/a>.<\/strong><\/p>","body":"<p>Despite significant socio-economic strides, the question of security &ndash; human, state and regional - remains a persistent challenge in much of Africa. Foreign actors from all corners of the globe have had varying degrees of security presence on the continent, ranging from military interventions to capacity building, and from project funding to trade in arms and equipment.<\/p>\r\n<p>Much of this foreign presence, however, has come either from individual countries or else from already established regional organisations, like the European Union. Far less has involved cooperation between more disparate actors, such as those representing either side of the North and South economic divide. This paper thus seeks to explore nascent trends in North&ndash;South security cooperation in Africa&rsquo;s Atlantic region, with a particular focus on the regions represented by the Southern African Development Community (SADC) and the Economic Community of West Africa States (ECOWAS). Is an Atlantic area for cooperation forming? Some progress in domains such as maritime security is already discernible. This paper also identifies further areas for cooperation. Atlantic cooperation in Africa is an idea with rich possibilities.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Download the paper here:<\/strong>&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"316","shares":"0","tweets":"4","mails":"3","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2014-09-29 12:38:00","modified":"2016-02-08 11:15:35"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"66","content_id":"324","type":"1","file_name":"324-ATLANTIC FUTURE_06_The Atlantic as a new security area.pdf","description":"Scientific paper no. 6: \"The Atlantic as a new security area? Current engagements and prospects for security cooperation between Africa and its Atlantic counterparts\"","created":"2014-09-29 12:39:50","modified":"2014-09-29 12:39:50"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"4174","content_id":"324","tag_id":"21","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"21","code":"security","name":"Security","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"C31F4A","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:08:37"}},{"id":"4168","content_id":"324","tag_id":"21","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"21","code":"security","name":"Security","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"C31F4A","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:08:37"}},{"id":"4169","content_id":"324","tag_id":"126","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"126","code":"cooperation","name":"Cooperation","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-30 10:21:56","modified":"2013-09-30 10:21:56"}},{"id":"4170","content_id":"324","tag_id":"140","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"140","code":"africa","name":"Africa","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:33","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:33"}},{"id":"4171","content_id":"324","tag_id":"130","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"130","code":"human-security","name":"Human security","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-10 11:59:29","modified":"2013-10-10 11:59:29"}},{"id":"4172","content_id":"324","tag_id":"178","order":"5","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"178","code":"university-of-pretoria","name":"University of Pretoria","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2014-04-24 14:52:42","modified":"2014-04-24 14:52:42"}},{"id":"4173","content_id":"324","tag_id":"150","order":"6","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"4174","content_id":"324","tag_id":"21","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"21","code":"security","name":"Security","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"C31F4A","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:08:37"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"311","code":"technology--trade-and-transport-","user_id":"1","title":"Technology, Trade and Transport ","abstract":"<p><strong>ATLANTIC FUTURE scientific paper no. 5 is out: \"Technology, Trade and Changes in Transport in the Atlantic Space\", by N. Barron, S. McGuire and N. Perdikis at<\/strong>&nbsp;<strong><a href=\"http:\/\/www.aber.ac.uk\/en\/\">Aberystwyth University<\/a> and S. Khorana at Keele University<\/strong><\/p>","body":"<p>This paper asks what is required to develop resurgence in trade and economic integration in the Atlantic economy. It does this by examining the factors that have led to growth in the past and examines the current network of transport links; in particular maritime networks. The paper outlines demand and supply based drivers. It finds on the demand side that the growth of national GDP&rsquo;s has led not only to an increase in goods transported but also to a change in the composition of those goods. Growing GDP has also influenced the mode of transport used to&nbsp;carry goods. Other demand side factors that have influenced the growth of trade include lower trade barriers as a result of trade agreements; the entry into the world economy of former centrally planned command economies as well as the emerging BRICS and NICs and the operations of multinational companies. On the supply side the main influence in promoting networks include the decline in transportation costs brought about by technological changes affecting ships and aircraft coupled with the increase in investment in sea ports and airports as well as the associated development of hub and spoke networks. The development and use of the internet connections has also boosted trade in goods. To regenerate the Atlantic economy will require inter-governmental cooperation to develop economic and political institutions to facilitate economic integration and growth and improve transport networks in the Atlantic economic space.<\/p>","views":"185","shares":"0","tweets":"1","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2014-09-23 12:54:00","modified":"2016-02-06 02:13:49"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"65","content_id":"311","type":"1","file_name":"311-ATLANTIC FUTURE_05_Technology, Trade and Changes in Transport in the.pdf","description":"Scientific paper no. 5: \"Technology, Trade and Changes in Transport in the Atlantic Space\"","created":"2014-09-23 12:55:27","modified":"2014-09-23 12:55:27"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"7296","content_id":"311","tag_id":"20","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"20","code":"economy-and-finance","name":"Economy and finance","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"A85CA0","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-09-27 09:57:02"}},{"id":"7292","content_id":"311","tag_id":"78","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"78","code":"transport","name":"Transport","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 10:52:35","modified":"2013-09-27 10:52:35"}},{"id":"7293","content_id":"311","tag_id":"161","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"161","code":"maritime-transport","name":"maritime transport","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"7294","content_id":"311","tag_id":"16","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"16","code":"trade","name":"Trade","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 10:26:12","modified":"2013-09-27 10:26:12"}},{"id":"7295","content_id":"311","tag_id":"150","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"7296","content_id":"311","tag_id":"20","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"20","code":"economy-and-finance","name":"Economy and finance","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"A85CA0","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-09-27 09:57:02"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"310","code":"global-value-chains-in-the-atlantic","user_id":"1","title":"Global Value Chains in the Atlantic","abstract":"<p><strong>ATLANTIC FUTURE scientific paper no. 4 is out: \"Global Value Chains in the Atlantic Space\", by Mariana Magaldi de Sousa and Elsy Gonzalez Cubr&iacute;a at<\/strong>&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/www.cide.edu\/\"><strong>CIDE<\/strong><\/a><\/p>","body":"<p>Global value chains (GVCs) have revolutionized trade. Countries no longer have to produce a particular product from scratch; all they must do is insert themselves into an existing chain of production that often spreads across several countries. Nevertheless, insertion into a global value chain has become a real challenge. Economies that are not able to successfully insert&nbsp;themselves into multiple GVCs are likely to reduce their opportunities for industrialization and economic growth. The purpose of this paper is to investigate the extent to which countries in the Atlantic Space have inserted themselves into GVCs in the past two decades. It draws on an original dataset of trade patterns by stage of production and value added that spans from 1995 to 2012, collected from the UN COMTRADE databank and the OECD-WTO Trade in Value Added (TiVA) dataset. It finds that despite some interesting cross-country variation, participation in GVCs is still generally low. The paper proceeds as follows. In Section 2, we review the concept of value chain participation and alternative methodologies for measuring it. Section 3 provides a panoramic view of trade flows in the Atlantic, and Section 4 focuses on empirical evidence of GVC participation in two case studies (Mexico and Brazil). Section 5 briefly assesses the available information on trade in value added in selected countries of the Atlantic space and the last Section concludes.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;<\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Download the paper here:<\/strong>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"344","shares":"0","tweets":"2","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2014-09-23 12:50:00","modified":"2016-02-05 16:19:15"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"64","content_id":"310","type":"1","file_name":"310-ATLANTIC FUTURE_04_Global Value Chains in the Atlantic Space.pdf","description":"Scientific paper no. 4: \"Global value chains in the Atlantic Space\"","created":"2014-09-23 12:50:39","modified":"2014-09-23 12:50:39"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"4182","content_id":"310","tag_id":"20","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"20","code":"economy-and-finance","name":"Economy and finance","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"A85CA0","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-09-27 09:57:02"}},{"id":"4179","content_id":"310","tag_id":"16","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"16","code":"trade","name":"Trade","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 10:26:12","modified":"2013-09-27 10:26:12"}},{"id":"4180","content_id":"310","tag_id":"153","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"153","code":"centro-de-investigacion-y-docencia-economicas-ac-cide","name":"Centro de Investigaci\u00f3n y Docencia Econ\u00f3micas A.C. (CIDE)","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-10 15:01:11","modified":"2013-12-10 15:01:11"}},{"id":"4181","content_id":"310","tag_id":"150","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"4182","content_id":"310","tag_id":"20","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"20","code":"economy-and-finance","name":"Economy and finance","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"A85CA0","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-09-27 09:57:02"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"309","code":"trade-governance-in-the-atlantic","user_id":"1","title":"Trade governance in the Atlantic","abstract":"<p><strong>ATLANTIC FUTURE scientific paper no. 3 is out: \"Multilateral Agreements and Global Governance of International Trade Regimes\", by S. McGuire and N. Perdikis at<\/strong>&nbsp;<strong><a href=\"http:\/\/www.aber.ac.uk\/en\/\">Aberystwyth University<\/a> and S. Khorana at Keele University<\/strong><\/p>","body":"<p>This paper conceptualises how trade governance is evolving within regional trading agreements (RTAs) in the Atlantic Space. Two main research questions are posed: Can Atlantic Space agreements connect the bilateral and multilateral trade frameworks and contribute to a new framework on global trade governance? What are the areas of convergence and divergence between RTAs negotiated in the Atlantic Space and the WTO Agreements? Findings reveal that: firstly, trade liberalisation commitments undertaken with in the Atlantic Space by partner countries are driven by the aim of achieving convergence on trade rules between RTAs with WTO Agreements. Some agreements are, however, aspirational in nature. Second, the degree of trade governance convergence between Atlantic space trading arrangements and the WTO Agreements depends on the level of partner countries&rsquo; development and their integration into the world economy, suggesting that RTAs with countries that are well integrated into the world economy tend to exhibit greater convergence to WTO Agreements. However, there is a clear trend of an overlap between RTAs and WTO Agreements which can be interpreted to mean that regional agreements could support the Atlantic Space&rsquo;s role as a global actor to shape a functioning multilateral order.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Download the paper here:<\/strong>&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"249","shares":"1","tweets":"4","mails":"1","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2014-09-23 12:44:00","modified":"2016-02-06 03:24:44"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"63","content_id":"309","type":"1","file_name":"309-ATLANTIC FUTURE_03_Multilateral Agreements and Global Governance of International Trade Regimes.pdf","description":"Scientific paper no. 3: \"Multilateral Agreements and Global Governance of International Trade Regimes\"","created":"2014-09-23 12:45:22","modified":"2014-09-23 12:45:22"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"4190","content_id":"309","tag_id":"20","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"20","code":"economy-and-finance","name":"Economy and finance","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"A85CA0","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-09-27 09:57:02"}},{"id":"4187","content_id":"309","tag_id":"88","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"88","code":"governance","name":"Governance","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 10:55:35","modified":"2013-09-27 10:55:35"}},{"id":"4188","content_id":"309","tag_id":"165","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"165","code":"aberystwyth-university-wales-uk","name":"Aberystwyth University Wales (UK)","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2014-01-15 10:50:33","modified":"2014-01-15 10:50:33"}},{"id":"4189","content_id":"309","tag_id":"150","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"4190","content_id":"309","tag_id":"20","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"20","code":"economy-and-finance","name":"Economy and finance","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"A85CA0","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-09-27 09:57:02"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"308","code":"commercial-ties-in-the-atlantic","user_id":"1","title":"Commercial ties in the Atlantic","abstract":"<p><strong>ATLANTIC FUTURE scientific paper no. 2 is out: \"<\/strong><strong>Commercial Ties in the Atlantic Basin: The Evolving Role of Services and Investment<\/strong><strong>\", by Daniel S. Hamilton at&nbsp;<\/strong><strong><a href=\"http:\/\/transatlantic.sais-jhu.edu\/\">CTR<\/a>&nbsp;<\/strong>(<strong>Center for Transatlantic Relations at Johns Hopkins University's School of Advanced International Studies)<\/strong><\/p>","body":"<p>More services and investments flow among economies within the Atlantic Hemisphere than among those in the Asian Hemisphere. Services are the sleeping giant of the pan-Atlantic economy. The Atlantic is home to the world's major services economies; Atlantic economies are each other's most important services markets; and Atlantic economies are poised to be major beneficiaries and drivers of the growth in global services. Services are not just a North Atlantic story; they represent a growing area of commercial activity among Southern Atlantic countries as well, particularly in energy related services; engineering and construction services; and education and managerial services. The United States and Europe are global leaders as outward investors and recipients. But today a rising global share of FDI emanates from the developing nations. And whereas trade and investment ties, and bank lending, between these nations and Africa and South and Central America were once shallow and underdeveloped, such linkages are now thicker, more robust and more sophisticated, particularly from China. But the EU remains the largest source of FDI on all Atlantic continents. It is also the largest holder of portfolio assets in North America. Its assets in Africa are roughly equal to those of Asia. North America accounted for over half of South and Central America's portfolio holdings in 2012, with the EU the only other major asset holder. South and Central America's holdings in North America and Europe grew rapidly over the past decade, although from a low base. All told, the Atlantic Hemisphere accounted for 83.8% of EU portfolio assets and 70.2% of North American portfolio assets in 2012.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Download the paper here:<\/strong>&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"253","shares":"0","tweets":"2","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2014-09-23 12:27:00","modified":"2016-02-03 21:19:29"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"61","content_id":"308","type":"1","file_name":"308-ATLANTIC FUTURE_02_Commercial ties in the Atlantic Basin.pdf","description":"Scientific paper no. 2: \"Commercial Ties in the Atlantic Basin:\r\nThe Evolving Role of Services and Investment\"","created":"2014-09-23 12:28:39","modified":"2014-09-23 12:28:39"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"4195","content_id":"308","tag_id":"20","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"20","code":"economy-and-finance","name":"Economy and finance","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"A85CA0","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-09-27 09:57:02"}},{"id":"4191","content_id":"308","tag_id":"16","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"16","code":"trade","name":"Trade","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 10:26:12","modified":"2013-09-27 10:26:12"}},{"id":"4192","content_id":"308","tag_id":"160","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"160","code":"investment","name":"investment","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"4193","content_id":"308","tag_id":"125","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"125","code":"johns-hopkins-university-jhu","name":"Johns Hopkins University (JHU)","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-30 10:19:12","modified":"2013-09-30 10:19:12"}},{"id":"4194","content_id":"308","tag_id":"150","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"4195","content_id":"308","tag_id":"20","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"20","code":"economy-and-finance","name":"Economy and finance","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"A85CA0","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-09-27 09:57:02"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"305","code":"direct-investment-flows-in-the-atlantic","user_id":"1","title":"Direct investment flows in the Atlantic","abstract":"<p>ATLANTIC FUTURE scientific paper no. 1 is out: \"Continuities and changes in patterns of direct investment flows between South America and Africa\", by Katarina Pereira da Costa at <a href=\"http:\/\/www.cesem.ma\/\">HEM-CESEM<\/a>.&nbsp;<\/p>","body":"<p>The countries of Africa and South America have been experiencing in the last years a substantial growth in their direct investment flows, deepening their integration into the international economy. Recently, we notice the emergence of new partners, who gained weight in Africa and South America direct investments flows, to the detriment of their traditional partners &ndash; the European Union (EU) and the United States (US). Both Africa and South America are diversifying their direct investments towards emerging countries, which includes deepening their own bilateral relationship. The main objective of this paper is to present a general analysis of direct investment relations between South America and Africa, and its relations with the world as well as with the two other important actors in the Atlantic space, the US and the EU. The paper also presents an analysis of Brazilian direct investments in Africa as well as a brief review of South African investments in Brazil.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Download the paper here:<\/strong>&nbsp;<\/p>","views":"231","shares":"1","tweets":"3","mails":"2","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2014-09-22 17:02:00","modified":"2016-02-02 17:02:29"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"62","content_id":"305","type":"1","file_name":"305-ATLANTIC FUTURE_01_Continuities and changes in patterns of direct investment flows between South America and Africa.pdf","description":"Scientific paper no. 1: \"Continuities and changes in patterns of direct investment flows between South America and Africa\"","created":"2014-09-23 12:30:16","modified":"2014-09-23 12:30:16"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"4204","content_id":"305","tag_id":"20","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"20","code":"economy-and-finance","name":"Economy and finance","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"A85CA0","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-09-27 09:57:02"}},{"id":"4196","content_id":"305","tag_id":"179","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"179","code":"south-africa","name":"South Africa","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2014-04-24 14:53:06","modified":"2014-04-24 14:53:06"}},{"id":"4197","content_id":"305","tag_id":"140","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"140","code":"africa","name":"Africa","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:33","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:33"}},{"id":"4198","content_id":"305","tag_id":"141","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"141","code":"latin-america","name":"Latin America","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:43","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:43"}},{"id":"4199","content_id":"305","tag_id":"149","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"149","code":"institut-des-hautes-etudes-de-management-hem","name":"Institut des Hautes Etudes de Management (HEM)","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-02 14:34:30","modified":"2013-12-02 14:34:30"}},{"id":"4200","content_id":"305","tag_id":"68","order":"5","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"68","code":"foreign-direct-investment","name":"Foreign direct investment","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 10:49:59","modified":"2013-09-27 10:49:59"}},{"id":"4201","content_id":"305","tag_id":"160","order":"6","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"160","code":"investment","name":"investment","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"4202","content_id":"305","tag_id":"194","order":"7","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"194","code":"direct-investment-flows","name":"direct investment flows","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"4203","content_id":"305","tag_id":"150","order":"8","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"150","code":"results","name":"Results","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-11 13:44:03","modified":"2013-12-10 14:14:40"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"4204","content_id":"305","tag_id":"20","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"20","code":"economy-and-finance","name":"Economy and finance","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"A85CA0","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-09-27 09:57:02"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"199","code":"an-atlantic-lunch-with-up-students","user_id":"1","title":"An Atlantic lunch with UP students","abstract":"<p style=\"margin-top: 0cm; margin-right: 0cm; margin-bottom: 18.75pt; margin-left: 0cm; line-height: 16.45pt; vertical-align: baseline;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: 'Open Sans','sans-serif'; color: #4c4c4c;\">The ATLANTIC FUTURE workshop in Pretoria was organized by GovInn (Centre for the Study of Governance Innovation), University of Pretoria, in June 2014. The workshop took place in the frame of the Governance Innovation Week, a series of seminars, workshops, roundtables and keynote lectures dealing with emerging trends in the field of regional integration, supranational governance, sustainable development, alternative economic thinking and civil society.<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: 0cm; margin-right: 0cm; margin-bottom: 18.75pt; margin-left: 0cm; line-height: 16.45pt; vertical-align: baseline; orphans: auto; text-align: start; widows: auto; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; word-spacing: 0px;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: 'Open Sans','sans-serif'; color: #4c4c4c;\">As part of the Workshop, a working lunch with thirty-six prominent UP Young Innovators was held to discuss several issues related to the Atlantic.<\/span><\/strong><\/p>","body":"<p>As part of the ATLANTIC FUTURE project, GovInn (Centre for the Study of Governance Innovation), University of Pretoria, organised a working lunch on 7 June 2014. Thirty six prominent students or &lsquo;UP Young Innovators&rsquo; were selected to participate. These were international postgraduate students from a variety of different disciplines from across the University, including political science, engineering and the natural sciences.<\/p>\r\n<p>During the working lunch, the students had the opportunity to discuss some of the key themes of the ATLANTIC FUTURE such as security, the environment, institutional cooperation and migration, among others, with Project&rsquo;s senior researchers R. Andreas Kraemer (Ecologic Institute), Camila Pastor (CIDE), In&ecirc;s Sousa (FGV), and Madeleine Goerg (GMF). Each table gathered around 8 to 10 prominent UP Young Innovators.<\/p>\r\n<p>The ATLANTIC FUTURE working lunch started with opening remarks by Jordi Vaquer (CIDOB), in which he presented the ATLANTIC FUTURE project in a global context. The discussions in each of the tables revolved around the following topics:&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p>The table chaired by In&ecirc;s Catarina Pereira da Costa Sousa (FGV) focused on <strong>security in the Atlantic<\/strong>. Far from being homogeneous, the Atlantic Basin combines different historical and cultural backgrounds, diverse natural features, and distinct levels of development. While these favour numerous economic and political opportunities, they may represent an obstacle in tackling maritime security challenges. The maritime security in the Atlantic becomes strategically important to the North and South Atlantic in terms of resources, regulation of maritime system, prevention of international crime, territorial disputes, and control of terrorist activities. The redistribution and rebalancing of power occurring in the world drive the main stakeholders in the region to look at the Atlantic wider region as a potential space of cooperation. However, are the traditional Atlantic Basin powers (the US and the EU) willing to recognise these new actors? The lunchtime discussions addressed this and other related questions. For example, are Atlantic Basin countries willing to make the Atlantic a priority when formulating their foreign policies? Why is it relevant to look at the Atlantic wider structure as a potential source of maritime security cooperation for Africa? Can we identify common strategic security interests in the Atlantic Basin countries?<\/p>\r\n<p>The table chaired by Camila Pastor (CIDE) focused on <strong>migration in the Atlantic<\/strong>. The discussions mainly concerned international migration in the Atlantic basin between 1990 and 2013, as well as the historical patterns characterizing Atlantic mobility that these two decades build on. Current human mobility is reminiscent of the intense Atlantic mobility in the late nineteenth century but the patterns have changed significantly, as have the means of tracking migration, of regulating it, and of requesting migrants&rsquo; political and cultural commitment to their host countries. In addition, the discussions started with a brief overview of the history of the Atlantic basin as a social space structured by mobility and then also focused on global patterns and concerns around migration.<\/p>\r\n<p>The table chaired by Madeleine Goerg (GMF) focused on <strong>institutional cooperation in the Atlantic<\/strong>. The past decade has seen a broad rebalancing of power and a growing assertiveness of the global South. As hierarchies are redefined and interactions between states redrawn, the Atlantic basin brings the enduring dichotomy between North and South into perspective by pointing to nuanced and complex relations in the realm of institutional cooperation. This discussion sought to address some of the key dynamics in institutional cooperation in the Atlantic basin. It tackled questions such as: with the rise of countries like Brazil and South Africa, how have changing economic dynamics impacted existing forms cooperation? In which policy areas is cooperation most desirable and most effective and at which level? What institutional factors, facilitate or hinder cooperation, and what are the main sources of tension and factors for political cooperation in the current context?<\/p>\r\n<p>The table chaired by R. Andreas Kraemer (Ecologic Institute) focused on <strong>shared environmental issues in the Atlantic<\/strong>. R. Andreas Kraemer started the discussion by summarizing the Atlantic-specific, regional dynamics of global environmental challenges. He explained that the pan-Atlantic is not an abstract of international relations, but a biophysical reality. Beyond a shared physical environment, Atlantic Basin countries also share common histories and starting points. The table then attempted to address whether the interconnected Atlantic space helps to resolve, or instead worsen, shared environmental challenges. On the whole, it was thought that there is high potential for inter-Basin cooperation on resource management based on such similarities and on mutual challenges and interests.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p>Download the report here:<\/p>","views":"441","shares":"1","tweets":"1","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2014-06-14 09:00:00","modified":"2016-02-08 08:10:58"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"59","content_id":"199","type":"1","file_name":"199-Working lunch with UP Young Innovators.pdf","description":"","created":"2014-06-13 13:03:25","modified":"2014-06-13 13:03:25"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"3196","content_id":"199","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"3187","content_id":"199","tag_id":"109","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"109","code":"environment","name":"Environment","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 11:06:53","modified":"2013-09-27 11:06:53"}},{"id":"3188","content_id":"199","tag_id":"26","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"26","code":"resources-and-environment","name":"Resources and environment","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"9AC4AB","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:08:22"}},{"id":"3189","content_id":"199","tag_id":"190","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"190","code":"r-andreas-kraemer","name":"r. andreas kraemer","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"3190","content_id":"199","tag_id":"21","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"21","code":"security","name":"Security","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"C31F4A","created":"2013-10-21 17:29:28","modified":"2013-09-27 10:08:37"}},{"id":"3191","content_id":"199","tag_id":"126","order":"5","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"126","code":"cooperation","name":"Cooperation","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-30 10:21:56","modified":"2013-09-30 10:21:56"}},{"id":"3192","content_id":"199","tag_id":"94","order":"6","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"94","code":"migration","name":"Migration","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 10:57:01","modified":"2013-09-27 10:57:01"}},{"id":"3193","content_id":"199","tag_id":"5","order":"7","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"5","code":"atlantic-space","name":"Atlantic space","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"FFFFFF","created":"2013-09-27 09:55:08","modified":"2013-09-27 09:55:08"}},{"id":"3194","content_id":"199","tag_id":"189","order":"8","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"189","code":"govinn","name":"govinn","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"3195","content_id":"199","tag_id":"178","order":"9","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"178","code":"university-of-pretoria","name":"University of Pretoria","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2014-04-24 14:52:42","modified":"2014-04-24 14:52:42"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"3196","content_id":"199","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"198","code":"roundtable-atlantic-in-a-changing-world","user_id":"1","title":"Roundtable: Atlantic in a changing world","abstract":"<p style=\"margin-top: 0cm; margin-right: 0cm; margin-bottom: 18.75pt; margin-left: 0cm; line-height: 16.45pt; vertical-align: baseline;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: 'Open Sans','sans-serif'; color: #4c4c4c;\">The ATLANTIC FUTURE workshop in Pretoria was organized by GovInn (Centre for the Study of Governance Innovation), University of Pretoria, in June 2014. The workshop took place in the frame of the Governance Innovation Week, a series of seminars, workshops, roundtables and keynote lectures dealing with emerging trends in the field of regional integration, supranational governance, sustainable development, alternative economic thinking and civil society.<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: 0cm; margin-right: 0cm; margin-bottom: 18.75pt; margin-left: 0cm; line-height: 16.45pt; vertical-align: baseline; orphans: auto; text-align: start; widows: auto; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; word-spacing: 0px;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: 'Open Sans','sans-serif'; color: #4c4c4c;\">As part of the Workshop, a roundtable on \"The Atlantic in a changing world: emerging economic, social and political relations\", gathering different experts, was held.<\/span><\/strong><\/p>","body":"<p>The roundtable \"The Atlantic in a changing world: emerging economic, political and social relations\" was chaired by Frank Mattheis (GovInn, University of Pretoria) and was composed of the following experts:<\/p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Francis Kornegay (Senior Research Fellow at Institute for Global Dialogue)<\/li>\r\n<li>Sonia Lucarelli (Professor at University of Bologna)<\/li>\r\n<li>R. Andreas Kraemer (Atlantic Future, director of Ecologic Institute)<\/li>\r\n<li>Claudia S&aacute;nchez Bajo (PhD in Development Studies by ISS, The Hague, and Chair in Cooperative Enterprises)<\/li>\r\n<li>Antonio Fiori (Korea Foundation Endowment Chair at University of Bologna)<\/li>\r\n<li>Jordi Vaquer (Atlantic Future, former director of CIDOB and current director of Open Society Initiative for Europe)<\/li>\r\n<\/ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;The roundtable participants discussed several issues related to the Atlantic, such as the North-South divide, opportunities and conflicts in the Atlantic, the perspectives from South Africa, environmental issues or the role of Asia in the Atlantic, among others. One of the topics that drew more attention was the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) currently under negotiation between the EU and the US.<\/p>\r\n<p class=\"tab-image-container\"><img class=\"tab-image\" src=\"..\/..\/..\/..\/images\/contents\/198-1402656964.jpg\" alt=\"\" \/><\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p>The main ideas that emerged during the roundtable are summarized below.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Francis Kornegay<\/strong> talked of South Africa&rsquo;s role and its pivot position in the Southern sea lanes. In terms of geopolitics in the Atlantic, there exist major issues that need to be sorted out and, for that, there needs to be a North-South dialogue within the Atlantic. We need to look at different organizations, he said, that go beyond the North Atlantic.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Sonia Lucarelli<\/strong> spoke of how transatlantic relations have been limited to the North-North relations consolidated during the Cold War. We are currently in the process of deconstructing the concept of transatlantic relations limited to the North, so that it includes a wider, broader, space. But this process of deconstruction is still very preliminary and it has important limitations: there are strong differences such as the North-South divide but also great differences within the South; there are differences in the intensity of relations among the regions, such as economic relations (even if South-South trade has increased, the figures cannot be compared), and others such as migration patterns with huge migrations within the regions. In addition, there are also huge asymmetries in the relations between regions.<\/p>\r\n<p>Despite these weaknesses and limits, however, there is evidence of change in the Atlantic. The North-North line is strong, in spite of the economic crisis, the South-South is also gaining importance, and strategic relations are particularly important. There is need for more transatlantic cooperation, and enhanced dialogue is desperately needed, as there are common challenges that need to be handled together such as demographic trends or food scarcity.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>R. Andreas Kraemer&nbsp;<\/strong>wondered what will happen within the next years with Russia trying to bring back the Cold War dynamics and how will the Atlantic partnership react to that. He spoke of environmental and resources in the Atlantic. The Atlantic makes sense as a unit of analysis, he said, and although of course it is not a closed space, the Atlantic has its own internal dynamics. Regarding environment, R. Andreas Kraemer explained that the main actors in this arena are disruptive actors (the coal, gas, oil lobbies, etc.) and it does not appear to be a counterweight of pro-environmental actors. This asymmetry, he said, may lead to disaster. In particular, climate change will lead to disastrous consequences. He made another point referring to Brazil, an actor that keeps standing on the side and blocking any initiative. Brazil needs to engage, he affirmed.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Claudia S&aacute;nchez Bajo <\/strong>pointed that we are in a transition from thinking the Atlantic as a divided area, as a space of conquest, to thinking about it as a shared zone. There is an effort to make it a zone peace and free of nuclear weapons, which is a big difference with other oceans. For example, the South Atlantic was declared a &ldquo;Free-Zone&rdquo;, and that opened the way for multiple types of pacific cooperation. There is also a discourse of promoting democracy and human rights. Exchanges of values across the Atlantic have taken place. On another topic, she referred to the emergence of clusters of entrepreneurs from both sides, an interesting development that needs to be looked at.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Antonio Fiori<\/strong> referred to the pivot to Asia. From a Pacific perspective, he said, we need to look also from the other side and need to look at another pivot: the pivot of Asia into the Atlantic. The rise of the Pacific is influencing pan-Atlantic dynamics in a number of ways. Firstly, trade between Atlantic and non-Atlantic partners has boomed. China is one of the main actors here, one of the important trade partners in the Atlantic (it is present in Africa, in Latin America), and there are also other Asian partners such as South Korea or Malaysia. This, he pointed out, resembles traditional colonial patterns. For example, 90% of exports to China are commodities, and 90% of imported goods from China are manufactured goods. It is difficult not to think of becoming locked again in colonial-style relationships. Secondly, trade has also created new port facilities, in particular the Panama Canal, with China controlling the leases at both ends of the Canal. Thirdly, the melting ice in the Arctic is also crucial, as it is opening new routes of communication. It has shifted Atlantic and Pacific attention to the Arctic, and China is there. It is predicted that most of Chinese trade will be carried out through the Northern lines in the future.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Jordi Vaquer <\/strong>started his intervention by pointing that oceans divide and do not unite, except of course if one looks at the Ocean itself (in terms of ecological matters and other areas). He pointed at three other obvious aspects related to relations in the Atlantic. Firstly, there are at least two spaces: the North Atlantic and the South Atlantic; secondly, there are too many asymmetries between the North and the South; and thirdly, the Atlantic is not problematic enough so it does not attract attention, and there is no institutional framework of any meaning compared, for example, to APEC. So, he enquired, why should attention be paid to the Atlantic? In bi-ocean countries such as South Africa or Mexico, there is a choice. Why would Mexico pay attention to Africa, when everything is happening in Asia? However, missing their oceanic potential means missing opportunities. He spoke more specifically of the ATLANTIC FUTURE project, where the Atlantic is looked at as a space, as a point where regions meet, and as a microcosm of what is going on in the world. He carried on by raising the issue of the TTIP. Its signature may reconfigure global and European rules hugely. This could make it impossible for the Atlantic space to break tensions. In conclusion, there is opportunity in the Atlantic, but also real threats. In any case, it is worth exploring it. And by neglecting the Atlantic, we may find that it may become interesting for the wrong reasons, he concluded.<\/p>\r\n<p>After the participants&rsquo; interventions, a debate with the audience ensued around a number of topics and issues. R. Andreas Kraemer was of the opinion that oceans don&rsquo;t divide, as traditionally they have facilitated trade, transfer of ideas, etc. So oceans unite us more that they divide us. Francis Kornegay said that South Africa does not have a geostrategic conception of itself, and that if it did it would try to balance its Indian Ocean with its South Atlantic Ocean potential. On territorial conflicts, Jordi Vaquer pointed out that while the Malvinas issue is a problem in the Atlantic, this does not mean that it has to stop any kind of cooperation, as the Gibraltar conflict between Spain and UK does not, for example. Lorenzo Fioramonti (GovInn, University of Pretoria) enquired whether the Atlantic has a qualitative difference to make, and what it would be. The Atlantic, the participants replied, does make a qualitative difference as it has common understandings of many concepts and we could build on. This is the difference with Asia. Finally, the issue of TTIP was raised again. Valerio Briani (IAI) said that TTIP is probably one of the main things happening in the Atlantic after NATO. R. Andreas Kraemer said that the TTIP is the conflict between rights of corporations and the rights of the people, and the fact that we see it as a geographical thing is a mistake. Jordi Vaquer added that TTIP will have huge negative consequences outside, and it is an affront in Europe. It is an assault of corporate power against democracies, he concluded.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p>Download the Roundtable Report here:<\/p>","views":"429","shares":"0","tweets":"2","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2014-06-13 10:00:00","modified":"2016-02-05 15:46:16"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"57","content_id":"198","type":"1","file_name":"198-Rountable Report_Economic political and social relations.pdf","description":"","created":"2014-06-13 12:47:45","modified":"2014-06-13 12:47:45"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"3127","content_id":"198","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"3122","content_id":"198","tag_id":"186","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"186","code":"ttip","name":"ttip","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"3123","content_id":"198","tag_id":"187","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"187","code":"transatlantic-trade-and-investment-partnership","name":"transatlantic trade and investment partnership","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"3124","content_id":"198","tag_id":"189","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"189","code":"govinn","name":"govinn","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"3125","content_id":"198","tag_id":"178","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"178","code":"university-of-pretoria","name":"University of Pretoria","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2014-04-24 14:52:42","modified":"2014-04-24 14:52:42"}},{"id":"3126","content_id":"198","tag_id":"140","order":"5","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"140","code":"africa","name":"Africa","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:33","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:33"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"3127","content_id":"198","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"197","code":"roundtable-africa-in-the-atlantic","user_id":"1","title":"Roundtable: Africa in the Atlantic","abstract":"<p>The ATLANTIC FUTURE workshop in Pretoria was organized by GovInn (Centre for the Study of Governance Innovation), University of Pretoria, in June 2014. The workshop took place in the frame of the Governance Innovation Week, a series of seminars, workshops, roundtables and keynote lectures dealing with emerging trends in the field of regional integration, supranational governance, sustainable development, alternative economic thinking and civil society.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p>As part of the Workshop, a roundtable on \"What role for Africa in a new Atlantic area?\" that gathered a group of experts was held.<\/p>","body":"<p>The rountable \"What role for Africa in a new Atlantic area?\" was chaired by Dr Msukizi Qobo (GovInn, South Africa) and was composed of the following experts:&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Jakkie Cilliers (Executive Director of the Institute for Security Studies)<\/li>\r\n<li>Andrew Grant (Professor at Queen&rsquo;s University, Canada)<\/li>\r\n<li>Catherine Grant (South African Institute of International Affairs)<\/li>\r\n<li>Garth Le Pere (University of Pretoria)<\/li>\r\n<li>Brenan Vickers (Institute for Global Dialogue)<\/li>\r\n<\/ul>\r\n<p>The roundtable participants discussed several issues related to the Atlantic, focusing on Africa. Again, one of the topics that drew more attention was the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) currently under negotiation between the EU and the US, and what implications it would have for Africa.<\/p>\r\n<p class=\"tab-image-container\"><img class=\"tab-image\" src=\"..\/..\/..\/..\/images\/contents\/197-1402655252.jpg\" alt=\"\" \/><\/p>\r\n<p>The main ideas that emerged during the roundtable are summarized below.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Jakkie Cilliers<\/strong> emphasized that there is very limited awareness of the Atlantic in Africa, except for the case of Morocco. South Africa, he pointed out, used to have an interest in the Atlantic but no longer has it. South Africa is interested in Asia, the EU and the US. The only real awareness is on overexploitation of resources largely by European companies. On the TTIP, Cilliers made remarks on the geostrategic implications. TTIP is an effort to maintain Western dominance. It changes economic dynamics and it has energy implications, which has a renewed momentum given the Russia - Ukraine issue. So, countries have two options: either to join this one third of the world, or to opt out. For Africa, because there are such low levels of internal trade, the implications of TTIP would be that may force regional integration in Africa, and also force Africa to look further into Asia and the Pacific, because TTIP will cause loss of trade for Africa. For the future of the Atlantic, discussions need to take hard geostrategic drivers into consideration. Countries in the South Atlantic remain much less important countries in this future world, he said.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Andrew Grant <\/strong>spoke aboutaspects that do not get much attention, such as the Kimberly process on diamonds.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Catherine Grant<\/strong> also referred to the TTIP. She said that the reality of economic linkages of South Africa is that there are strong investment ties with the US and the EU. This is not an ideal picture, she said, but it is South Africa&rsquo;s real picture (with the exception of China). And, she added, there is no particular role of Africa in an emerging Atlantic space, as this is very much dominated by the Northern Atlantic. Africa would not favour Atlantic space over other alliances, because we are still seeing the failure of the US and the EU to carry out any real institutional reform in the economic space. When the space is dominated by these two players, and they are not prepared to recognize the changes in the world, why would Africa be interested in pursuing an Atlantic agenda, she wondered.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Garth Le Pere<\/strong> spoke of the two registers along which Africa can be placed in this emerging Atlantic: the instrumental and the normative one. The instrumental one is capitalist in spirit. The normative one is the US and the EU development cooperation agenda (good governance, institutions, etc.). Both tend to reinforce each other, he said. He also talked about the issue of climate change and pointed that Africa has very low and problematic adaptive responses.<\/p>\r\n<p><strong>Brendan Vickers<\/strong> said that African countries should engage Atlantic counterparts on African priorities. There are three things he considered to be the African priorities: firstly, structural transformation, as Africa needs to shift from export of commodities to a more sustainable growth; secondly, regional and continental integration; and thirdly, infrastructure development. These, he added, are going to require some kind of closer partnership with Atlantic partnership. He also pointed that it makes no sense to speak of one Atlantic region, as one needs to differentiate between North Atlantic and South Atlantic.<\/p>\r\n<p>After the participants&rsquo; interventions, a lively debate with the audience ensued around a number of topics and issues, particularly on the TTIP. In this sense, <strong>Lorenzo Fioramonti<\/strong> (GovInn, Univesrity of Pretoria), stated that the TTIP is the most astute way of dodging Doha. Is there an Africa proactive reaction to TTIP or are we just waiting for it to happen, he enquired. In Brendan Vickers&rsquo; view, the focus of US and EU is on TTIP, and it is about raising standards. There is very little Africans can do about TTIP, so Africans should focus on what they have control over, that is the regional and continental integration process. The priority should be infrastructure development, etc. There is a need to focus on the continental FTA. Africa needs to become an actor and not a pawn, he added.<\/p>\r\n<p>On another subject, Jakkie Cilliers referred to the idea of a single integrated Africa as a mirage. He also referred to demographics as something that will have a huge impact in the future. Africa is currently one billion people and will be two billion by 2050. On the other hand, Europe is 500 million now and will remain 500 million by 2050. This is something to reflect about, he concluded.<\/p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p>Download the Rountable Report here:<\/p>","views":"269","shares":"0","tweets":"2","mails":"0","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2014-06-13 09:00:00","modified":"2016-02-03 01:53:50"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[{"id":"56","content_id":"197","type":"1","file_name":"197-Rountable Report_Africa in the Atlantic.pdf","description":"","created":"2014-06-13 12:28:08","modified":"2014-06-13 12:28:08"}],"ContentTag":[{"id":"3238","content_id":"197","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"3232","content_id":"197","tag_id":"140","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"140","code":"africa","name":"Africa","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-10-25 10:20:33","modified":"2013-10-25 10:20:33"}},{"id":"3233","content_id":"197","tag_id":"179","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"179","code":"south-africa","name":"South Africa","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2014-04-24 14:53:06","modified":"2014-04-24 14:53:06"}},{"id":"3234","content_id":"197","tag_id":"186","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"186","code":"ttip","name":"ttip","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"3235","content_id":"197","tag_id":"187","order":"4","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"187","code":"transatlantic-trade-and-investment-partnership","name":"transatlantic trade and investment partnership","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}},{"id":"3236","content_id":"197","tag_id":"178","order":"5","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"178","code":"university-of-pretoria","name":"University of Pretoria","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2014-04-24 14:52:42","modified":"2014-04-24 14:52:42"}},{"id":"3237","content_id":"197","tag_id":"189","order":"6","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"189","code":"govinn","name":"govinn","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":null,"created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"}}],"MainCategory":{"ContentTag":{"id":"3238","content_id":"197","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},"Format":[]},{"Content":{"id":"54","code":"seminar-for-young-researchers-in-mexico","user_id":"1","title":"SEMINAR FOR YOUNG RESEARCHERS IN MEXICO","abstract":"<p>On 21 February 2014, CIDE organised a seminar with students of International Relations with an interest in the subject of Atlantic. More than 50 students attended the seminar. Several senior ATLANTIC FUTURE researchers participated in the seminar: R. Andreas Kraemer at Ecologic Institute (Germany), Alfredo Valladao at HEM (Morocco), Paul Isbell at Johns Hopkins University (United States) and Mark Aspinwall at CIDE (Mexico). Lorena Ruano at CIDE (Mexico) acted as the moderator.<\/p>","body":"<p>Lorena Ruano (CIDE) presented the ATLANTIC FUTURE project to the students, highlighting its main features. Next, Alfredo Valladao (HEM) spoke about the strengths of the Atlantic. While everybody talks about the Pacific and the emergence of China, he expressed to be sceptical about that. It is the Atlantic century we are going to see coming up, he noted, and not only the North Atlantic but the South Atlantic too. He made the following points: <strong>the new reserves of energy are in the Atlantic, and energy is the core of development and economic life.<\/strong> There is a huge basin of energy that can put us together and make the Atlantic one of the centres of energy producing of the world. Furthermore, North America and South America are the biggest food producers in the world. Africa and Latin America still have a huge stock of free land and water. There are environmental problems, he conceded, but <strong>we can see the Atlantic as a bread basket for the world<\/strong>. That is a huge area where we can have good cooperation. Thirdly, <strong>the Atlantic is home to huge consumer markets<\/strong>. The US alone represents about 1\/3 of the final private consumer, while China only accounts for 4-5% of the world&rsquo;s private consumption. In a world where consumption leads production, the Atlantic will play an enormous role of consumer market for the world&rsquo;s production. Some countries in Africa are developing fast, which will be a huge opportunity for business, cross-interests, production, consumers, etc. But more important, we are living today a real industrial revolution: from the old model of production chains of mass production for mass consumption to new model: that of ICT tech, 3D printing, advanced robotics, etc. That will be very difficult to replicate in some countries in Asia like China, while in the Atlantic there are a lot of possibilities to do that, where societies open enough to be part of this ICT, to be part of it and take advantage of it. Atlantic will probably be the core of the new revolution of the world. Future economic production and consumption will be more centred in the Atlantic.&nbsp; He clarified, though, that this does not mean that it has to be against the Pacific.<\/p>\r\n<p>Paul Isbell (JHU) added that the <strong>Atlantic<\/strong><strong> is a new unit of analysis as well as a tool for new forms of international collaboration<\/strong>. Coming from a view of the Pacific rise, energy dependence to the Middle East, and the rise of the global South, he explained how when drawing an energy map, it revealed that most mental maps that had to do with the Atlantic and energy were either incorrect or beginning to change dramatically. There is a boom in Atlantic energy resources, reserves, in production, shale revolution, the rising role of gas, and other related forms of energy. The Atlantic is almost self-sufficient in energy. <strong>The energy story is really an Atlantic one<\/strong>, he concluded.<\/p>\r\n<p>Mark Aspinwall (CIDE) added how colonisation had a profound effect in linking together Europe, Africa and the Americas. <strong>The Atlantic is a coherent and fundamentally linked area, where there are important flows in terms of values and ideas<\/strong>. The whole idea of international collaboration and international rules is an Atlantic idea and continue to be generated in the Atlantic in an important way. In terms of economics, there has been a huge increase in services, trade and investment in the Atlantic. In terms of security, continued Lorena Ruano (CIDE), NATO is the main military alliance we have today with the most important capacity in terms of military gear and coordination. But one cannot forget that when thinking about the Atlantic, we mostly think of the North Atlantic. The most important economic exchanges happen in the North Atlantic. <strong>The North Atlantic is still dominant but the fastest rising links are in the South Atlantic<\/strong>, especially between Brazil and Africa. The South Atlantic, she concluded, is coming into the picture very fast.<\/p>\r\n<p>In R. Andreas Kraemer&rsquo;s view (Ecologic Institute), the Atlantic story remains strong. Something very important to consider is <strong>the role of China in the Atlantic<\/strong> today. He also made the point that energy systems, all technology providers, all big companies, are Atlantic, which is very disruptive for the environment. But <strong>there is also a problem of solving capacity<\/strong>. In natural resources there is also disruption (with overfishing, destroyed ecosystems, etc.)&nbsp;&nbsp; But if we try to find the best practices, we find them in the North East Atlantic. We can look at them and apply them in other places.<\/p>\r\n<p>Alfredo Valladao (HEM) pointed at one specific problem: there are many challenges. In terms of civil society, things are going quite well: <strong>there is a huge interchange of values, ideas, and people in the Atlantic<\/strong>. And because there is a lot of freedom of travelling and information, the Atlantic is the cradle of cosmopolitan society. In the business sphere, there are a lot of things going on, services and investment, lot of cross investment in countries in the Atlantic. The real challenge is institutionalizing the dialogue, because of bad perceptions. <strong>The Atlantic probably is the space with more regional integration schemes<\/strong>. Brazil is the &ldquo;big guy&rdquo; in the South Atlantic. While it still sees the South Atlantic as its own, it does not have the capabilities to manage it. It is very important to have a real dialogue with Brazil. And Africa is also key. Finally, he referred to the potential for new form of collaboration. Instead of trying to make big schemes, we should concentrate in solving concrete and specific problems together, such as drug trafficking. To sum up, we should look at solvable problems that are Atlantic.<\/p>\r\n<p>An interesting debate with the students ensued. Questions such as the role of Mexico in the Atlantic, what were the effects of being a dual basin country, or the level of institutionalism in the Atlantic were only a few of them.<\/p>\r\n<p>Check photos of the Seminar for Young Researchers below:<\/p>\r\n<p class=\"tab-image-container\">&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n<p class=\"tab-image-container\"><img class=\"tab-image\" src=\"..\/..\/..\/..\/images\/contents\/54-1395739895.jpg\" alt=\"\" \/>&nbsp; &nbsp;<img class=\"tab-image\" style=\"font-family: 'Open Sans', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 21.920000076293945px;\" src=\"..\/..\/..\/..\/images\/contents\/54-1395740829.jpg\" alt=\"\" \/><\/p>\r\n<p class=\"tab-image-container\"><img class=\"tab-image\" src=\"..\/..\/..\/..\/images\/contents\/54-1395740339.jpg\" alt=\"\" \/>&nbsp; &nbsp;<img class=\"tab-image\" src=\"..\/..\/..\/..\/images\/contents\/54-1395741703.jpg\" alt=\"\" \/><\/p>\r\n<p class=\"tab-image-container\"><img class=\"tab-image\" src=\"..\/..\/..\/..\/images\/contents\/54-1395741302.jpg\" alt=\"\" \/>&nbsp;&nbsp;<img class=\"tab-image\" src=\"..\/..\/..\/..\/images\/contents\/54-1395742732.jpg\" alt=\"\" \/><\/p>","views":"266","shares":"0","tweets":"1","mails":"2","published":true,"image":true,"featured":true,"type":"0","created":"2014-03-24 14:54:00","modified":"2016-02-01 20:22:23"},"User":{"id":"1","email":"info@onebigrobot.com","first_name":"Administrator","last_name":null,"password":"c8d482e69d7de06cc7429d3b9484c8145fdfb818","code":"","role":"0","type":"0","published":true,"created":"2014-06-26 10:44:32","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00"},"Event":{"id":null,"datetime":null,"country":null,"city":null,"address":null,"map":null},"Resource":[],"ContentTag":[{"id":"2694","content_id":"54","tag_id":"44","order":"0","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"44","code":"the-atlantic1","name":"The Atlantic","type":"1","mandatory":true,"color":"0068AD","created":"2013-10-30 14:16:17","modified":"2013-08-02 12:27:19"}},{"id":"2675","content_id":"54","tag_id":"153","order":"1","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"153","code":"centro-de-investigacion-y-docencia-economicas-ac-cide","name":"Centro de Investigaci\u00f3n y Docencia Econ\u00f3micas A.C. (CIDE)","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-10 15:01:11","modified":"2013-12-10 15:01:11"}},{"id":"2676","content_id":"54","tag_id":"149","order":"2","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"149","code":"institut-des-hautes-etudes-de-management-hem","name":"Institut des Hautes Etudes de Management (HEM)","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-02 14:34:30","modified":"2013-12-02 14:34:30"}},{"id":"2677","content_id":"54","tag_id":"124","order":"3","created":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","modified":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","Tag":{"id":"124","code":"ecologic-institute-gmbh-ecologic","name":"Ecologic Institute GmbH (ECOLOGIC)","type":"0","mandatory":false,"color":"#FFFFFF","created":"2013-12-02 14:28:09","modified":"2013-12-02 14:28:09"}},{"id":"2678","content_id":"54","tag_id":"125","order":"4","created":"00